<HEADLINE> Russia Urges Suspension of Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Wednesday reiterated Moscow's call for a suspension of
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Moscow regards it "as an intermediate step that in its final
account should lead to their complete lifting," said Ivanov
following talks here with visiting Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tareq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said the permanent members of the U.N. Security Council have
made a certain amount of progress in coordinating their positions
on the draft resolution on Iraq, but no complete understanding has
been achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, for his part, described a draft resolution initiated by
Britain and the Netherlands on Iraq and being considered by the U.
N. Security Council as a "rotten document that imposes new terms
on Iraq and infringes on its sovereignty," the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has made the decision not to accept this document and"
urges our Russian friends to prevent its adoption," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who arrived here Tuesday on a four-day working visit,
also met with Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
