<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Opposes U.S. Provides Food Supply to SPLA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Sudan has officially declared
its opposition to a U.S. decision to provide food aid to John
Garang-led rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
Sudan deemed the move as threatening its national security,
according to an official press release read by Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Ali Abdul-Rahman Numeiri on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The move shows U.S. administration's disrespect of the United
Nations Charter," Numeiri said, adding that it was a breach of the
internationally-accepted principles and rules.
</P>
<P>
Under the rules, any mechanism on the humanitarian arena should
be channeled through the U.N., Sudan and the U.N. have agreed on
a definite mechanism, namely the "life line operation," for
offering food supplies to southern Sudan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has been locked in a 16-year-old civil war between
Sudanese government and the north opposition parties and the south
SPLA. The devastating war and ensuing famine have claimed nearly 2
million lives in the poor African country.
</P>
<P>
A Egyptian-Libyan initiative for Sudanese national
reconciliation is under discussion.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decision will create a food gap in Sudan and a
humanitarian crisis, so it is challenged by many human relief
organizations whether governmental or non-governmental, according
to the press release.
</P>
<P>
Some of the organizations declared their intention to stop
cooperation with the U.S. administration in its endeavor to supply
the SPLA with direct relief materials.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. move is in line with the U.S. decision to bombard the
Shifa' Pharmaceutical plant in Khartoum and to use the weapon of
food supplies against Sudan as well as impose unjust sanctions on
Sudan for groundless accusations, Numeiri pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Sudan is contacting with various world organizations and
countries to explain the state of the affairs and being ready for
explaining the situation before international and regional
organizations as a prelude to pass a resolution against the
U.S. decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
