<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urges to Break Conspiracy of Silence Around AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday urged the international community to break
the conspiracy of silence around AIDS so as to bring the epidemic
under control.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the occasion of the World's AIDS Day,
December 1, Annan said "on this last World's AIDS Day of the 20th
century, we still have no cure for AIDS."
</P>
<P>
"HIV has infected more than 50 million people so far. Of them,
16 million have died already. This year alone, the epidemic
claimed a record of 2.6 million lives. And in Africa, for the
first time, infected women aged 15 to 49 outnumbered infected men,
" the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"Altogether, a staggering 11.2 million children have been
orphaned by AIDS since the start of the epidemic, As the number of
adult Aids grows, so will the number of orphans," said he.
</P>
<P>
Annan pointed out that lack of affection, close bonds,
education about healthy sexuality, and in addition, violence,
poverty and discrimination contributed to the high number of
children and young people infected with the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to battle the culture of shame. Hiding AIDS
behind a curtain of stigma helps to spread it. Speaking out about
AIDS helps slow it down," Annan added.
</P>
</TEXT>
