<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth Approves Transferring Power to N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua ) -- Britain's Queen Elizabeth
Wednesday formally approved the transfer of responsibilities from
London to Belfast, thus ending 27 years of direct rule of Northern
Ireland from London.
</P>
<P>
Uttering the single word "Approved" in a brief ceremony at
Buckingham Palace, the queen gave her backing to the legislation
transferring power to Northern Ireland after it was rushed through
parliament on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the queen's approval completed the legal
formalities and power would be formally transferred at midnight.
</P>
<P>
Responsibility for key issues such as health, education,
finance and culture will now pass to the assembly and locally
elected politicians, for the first time in a generation.
</P>
<P>
The move to end 27 years of direct rule, is one of the key
parts of the Good Friday Agreement peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Peers in the House of Lords first passed the motion on Tuesday
afternoon, sending it to the main legislative chamber, the House
of Commons, which passed it shortly after midnight. The MPs voted
by 318 to 10 to back devolution.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair hailed the setting up of a power-
sharing executive in Northern Ireland as "one huge giant step"
towards lasting peace, saying it was a significant breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Irish Junior Foreign Minister Liz O'Donnell arrived
at Stormont in Belfast on Wednesday for the inaugural meeting of
the North South Ministerial Council.
</P>
<P>
She announced that the first meeting of the new body after
devolution will be on December 30.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Northern Ireland Executive is due to meet for
the first time and will begin to take political responsibility for
most of the departments currently dealt with by Northern Ireland
Office direct rule ministers.
</P>
<P>
But with devolution little more than hours away the IRA has
said it is unhappy with the decommissioning timetable, underlining
the fragility of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Protestant unionists and Catholic republicans agreed to set up
a partnership government on Monday to run the province, the first
time the bitterly divided parties will have shared power.
</P>
<P>
Centuries of suspicion will have to be buried but a carefully
planned step-by-step deal appears to have ended 20 months of
political wrangling that paralyzed the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
