<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Appeals for Peace in Burundi at Early Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni Wednesday called for the restoration of peace in Burundi
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the regional summit in Arusha, northern Tanzania,
the president said that prolonging the peace process would in
effect prolong the suffering of the people of Burundi, according
to a press release issued by the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
He urged the parties involved in the conflict to address their
task urgently so that the region can attend to other urgent
problems.
</P>
<P>
Museveni cautioned Burundi about the indiscriminate violence
being meted out on combatants and civilians and all groups
involved in the conflict including the national army, saying all
regional leaders condemn this kind of violence.
</P>
<P>
The initiative on Burundi peace must succeed so that regional
problems are solved by homemade solutions, failure of which will
encourage outside intervention and it might lead to the
proliferation of conflicts in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, also chairman of the regional initiative on Burundi,
paid tribute to Julius Nyerere, late founding president of
Tanzania, praising him for bringing great dedication,
determination and vision to the regional efforts being pursued
today.
</P>
<P>
At the one-day summit, former South African President Nelson
Mandela was designated as the new mediator of the Burundi peace
process to continue the course pursued by Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts in Burundi are characterized by ethnic hatred and
killing. Ethnic reconciliation between the Hutus and Tutsis has
been regarded as the sole everlasting solution to the problem in
the African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
