<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia: No Plans to "Unfreeze" Ties With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian military
official said Wednesday that Moscow has no plans to unfreeze" ties
with NATO, an alliance that participated in the aggression against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian leadership has not given the Defense Ministry any
instructions to fully restore relations with NATO," said Colonel
General Leonid Ivashov, head of the ministry's Department for
International Military Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, neither Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, nor
Chief of Staff Anatoly Kvashnin will go to Brussels on December 2
and 3, when a meeting of the Russia-NATO Permanent Council and a
session of the Council of Euro-Atlantic Partnership are to be held.
</P>
<P>
Moscow froze its relations with NATO after the transatlantic
military bloc started its 78-day air strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
At present, contacts between the Russian Defense Ministry and
NATO are maintained exclusively within the framework of the
peacekeeping operation in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, Ivashov
said.
</P>
<P>
Interfax, citing diplomatic sources, said Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov also does not plan to attend a session of the
Russia-NATO Permanent Council at the level of foreign ministers,
scheduled for mid-December in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
NATO has repeatedly expressed its wish to resume full ties with
Russia, but Moscow remains adamant, especially amid mounting
pressure from NATO countries over its military campaign against
Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General George Robertson, in an interview with
Interfax Wednesday, again urged for full resumption of its
relations with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"I see no strategic alternative to developing the NATO-Russia
partnership. It is an indispensable pillar of a new European
security architecture," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must, at the turn of the millennium, bring NATO-Russian
relations back to a level commensurate with the challenges that we
face together. I am personally committed to this vital endeavor ,"
Robertson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
