<HEADLINE> 4,500 Iranians Visit Holy Shrines in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 4,500 Iranian pilgrims,
or five batches, have arrived in Iraq in the past week to
visit the holy shrines in this country, the Iraqi News Agency
INA reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These are the first batches of Iranian pilgrims who visit
Iraq since last year's fasting month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities provided all the necessary facilities
including transportation and accommodation for the visiting
Iranian pilgrims, said INA.
</P>
<P>
INA said that President Saddam Hussein has issued directives
allowing Iranian civilians to perform religious rituals at holy
shrines inside Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As the annual fasting month of Ramadan is drawing near,
Iranians begin to visit holy shrines for Shiite Muslims in Iraq's
Najaf, Kerbela, Samara, Barbylon and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought a bitter war between 1980 and 1988, during
which Iranian pilgrims were forbidden to enter Iraq to perform
religious rituals.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the two countries have started taking
measures to normalize ties. Iraq agreed to allow limited number
of Iranian pilgrims to visit the holy shrines inside Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
