<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 55 More Bodies Recovered From Shipwreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-five more bodies of
Dashun shipwreck victims were salvaged by 18:00 hours today as
recovery operations continued at the accident site near the coast
city of Yantai in Shandong Province for the fourth day.
</P>
<P>
The naval force of the Chinese People's Liberation Army
dispatched more than 100 officers and men in today's rescue
operation. The Yantai Garrison Command sent 200 people, including
60 retiring soldiers, to transport salvaged bodies.
</P>
<P>
Diver Gong Shoujie alone picked up 21 bodies.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of calm sea tonight, the leading group in
charge of the salvage operation has decided to send more divers
for underwater searching room by room on the wrecked ship.
</P>
<P>
With 262 passengers and 40 crew members on board, the Dashun,
owned by the Yantai Yanda Automobile Ferry Company, caught fire on
the afternoon of November 24 and was forced to turn back from its
course to the port of Dalian in Liaoning Province, northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The vessel sent out distress signals after flames were
discovered at 4:30 p.m. The ship sank at about midnight the same
day.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 people have been involved in the rescue effort.
Sources confirmed that 22 people have been rescued alive so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian, Vietnamese Leaders Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Vietnamese President
Tran Duc Luong and Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee held
a 75-minute meeting here on Wednesday with both sides emphasizing
the historical and cultural linkages between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders voiced their determination to add a "new
content" to the close and long-standing political relations and
agreed that special focus on enhancing cooperation was needed in
the fields of information technology, human resource development,
science and technology, energy and pharmaceuticals, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Luong, who arrived here earlier in the day for a five-day
visit, also met with Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan,
who told his guest that the prospects of economical and technical
cooperation between the two countries were "bright and immense."
</P>
<P>
Hanoi has expressed a strong desire to enter into "long-term
cooperation" with New Delhi in the fields of defense, trade and
science and technology while India has offered to collaborate with
Vietnam in setting up software centers in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh
city.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed four agreements Wednesday involving a
credit worth 13.95-million-U.S. dollars to Vietnam on concessional
terms and the setting up of two software development and training
centers in the two Vietnamese cities.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed by senior Indian and Vietnamese
officials in the presence of Luong and Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to exchange instruments of
ratification of the Bilateral Investment Promotion and Protection
Agreement signed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Another agreement between the foreign service institutes of the
two countries was to enhance exchanges of students, professors,
experts and research scholars.
</P>
<P>
Luong is the first Vietnamese president to visit India since
the late Vietnamese leader Ho Chi Minh's historic trip to India in
1958.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is keen to improve the trade balance which is heavily
in India's favor at a time when Hanoi was simplifying its
procedures for imports and exports and encouraging direct contact
with businessmen and industrialists.
</P>
<P>
India's exports to Vietnam, including medicines and
pharmaceutical goods, chemicals, spare parts for railways, sugar
factories, defense equipment and machinery, stood at 130 million
dollars this year while imports from that country were valued at a
mere 20 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
