<HEADLINE> Meeting on Cooperation Among SAARC Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 1 (Xinhua) -- About 160 politicians,
economists and diplomats from South Asia gathered here Wednesday
to discuss cooperation among the SAARC (South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation) countries.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is focusing on issues like sequential
steps towards a South Asian Economic Community, social cohesion in
the region, environmentally sustainable development, cooperation
on culture and in the field of energy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also discuss the role of parliamentarians and
political leaders in social and economic development and the
improvement of political understanding through comprehensive and
regular consultations among the SAARC countries.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the meeting, Prime Minister Krishna Prasad
Bhattarai stressed the need for the South Asian countries to
strengthen cooperation to face the challenges of the new century.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai said that as the people of the South Asia are weighed
down by economic and social difficulties, group cooperation is
needed for bringing about peace and prosperity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Describing SAARC as a common forum for regional cooperation
among the peoples of South Asia, Bhattarai said SAPTA (South Asian
Preferential Trading Arrangements) is functioning to promote
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
SAPTA came into operation in 1995 as a first step for SAARC to
realize free trade among its member countries. Under SAPTA, 5,700
products enjoy tariff concessions ranging from 7.5 to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1985 to promote economic cooperation and social
progress in South Asia, SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
Nepal, the Maldives, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
