<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Ushers in New Equity, Derivatives Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Singapore announced Wednesday
the inauguration of Singapore Exchange (SGX), a new equity and
derivatives market, to prepare its capital market for future
cut-throat competition.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the SGX formally declared the merger or
demutualization of the Stock Exchange of Singapore (SES) and the
Singapore International Monetary Exchange (SIMEX).
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) unveiled in November,
1998 the plan to merge the SES and SIMEX into a single integrated
privately-held stock company.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said the new exchange only meant at the moment a
nominal merger rather than the actual mix of operations which
still stay out of sight.
</P>
<P>
In launching the SGX, Singapore's Deputy Prime Minister Lee
Hsien Loong also announced sweeping measures to enhance the
competitiveness of the capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Those included revising capital requirements, broadening
brokerage scope and improving risk management.
</P>
<P>
Lee, also chairman of MAS, also announced the speeding up of
the liberalization of broking commissions in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He said these measures were part of a "bold but coordinated
plan to phase in competition, while ensuring that proper risk
management systems are in place."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the need to open up market access decisively over the
next 12 months, Lee noted that a larger number of trading parties
transacting freely will increase the liquidity and depth of the
market.
</P>
<P>
To allow market forces to determine rates, commissions on
trades will also be made freely negotiable by January 1, 2001, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
SGX's strategies aim to produce a Singapore-based, world-class
capital markets infrastructure, promoting a free flow of capital
across markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The infrastructure will provide multiple instruments, serving
issuers, investors and intermediaries across time-zones," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
