<HEADLINE> S.Africa Calls for Globalization in Favor of Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- South African deputy
president Jacob Zuma said on Wednesday that the globalization
should help narrow the gap between the developing and developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Southern African Trade and Investment Summit in
 Mozambican capital Maputo, he said that it is unacceptable that
while poverty is globalizing at an alarming pace for the majority,
wealth is being accumulated into fewer and fewer hands, according
to a press report reaching here..
</P>
<P>
"This does not augur well for sustainable economic development.
As the gap between the rich and the poor grows, we need to be
aware of, and establish, the extent to which globalization has the
potential to generate instability and suffering among our people,"
Zuma was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was clear that in the global village, it was not feasible
for any single country or sub-region to prosper as an island in a
sea of poverty and misery, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The economic development of South Africa, of the Southern
African Development Community and of the whole Africa continent
will therefore not benefit us alone, but Europe and the world, as
it will foster social stability, peace and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"It is important at this point in time to stress that what our
countries need is direct foreign investment, to create sustainable
development, rather than speculative investment that could
potentially harm our economies," Zuma added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
