<HEADLINE> Swiss President Calls for Efforts to Help Developing World in AIDS Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Swiss President Ruth Dreifuss
has called on the international community to improve AIDS
prevention programs in developing countries where millions of
people are under threat from HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"We must not accept a divide between rich countries, where HIV-
infected people receive the latest medical treatment, and a
majority of people in the world who do not have adequate access to
medical care," Dreifuss said Wednesday in a statement marking
World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
She said that education and improving the standing of women in
society should be key elements in such a prevention campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss president also warned the Swiss against complacency
and urged them not to underestimate the dangers of AIDS, even
though much progress had been made and AIDS infections were on the
decline domestically.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest report by the World Health Organization
and the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS, there are a
total of 33.6 million people living with HIV/AIDS around the world,
among whom 32.4 million are adults and 1.2 million children under
15 years of age.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 alone, 2.6 million people died of AIDS and 470,000 of
them were children under 15, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 11.2 million children have been orphaned
by AIDS by the end of 1999, according to a new report by the
United Nations Children's Fund and the UNAIDS published here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that by the end of the year 2000, the
number of AIDS orphans will rise to more than 13 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
