<HEADLINE> Cambodian PM Calls for Raising Govt's Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen announced Wednesday that the government will take measures to
raise its efficiency to attract more foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on the government's development strategy and
policy, Hun Sen rapped some government officials for corruption
and inefficiency, especially those in the Council for Development
of Cambodia (CDC).
</P>
<P>
"The corrupt dealings severely hindered the foreign investment
and the economic development of the nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, the inefficient and trivial formalities of
examination and approval caused the decrease in foreign
investment," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the government has decided, from now on,
to simplify the formalities of investment project approval, and
put the departments concerned together in the CDC to save time for
investors.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that the time allowed to examine and approve
investment projects will be reduced from 45 to 28 days.
</P>
<P>
According to the CDC's statistics, the government approved 739
projects worth about 5,350 million U.S. dollars from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the approved investment projects declined sharply
in 1999, down from 143 projects in 1998 to 80 through November
this year.
</P>
<P>
He also encouraged more and more foreign companies and
businessmen to invest in Cambodia's agriculture, communication,
electricity and energy as well as other areas. 
</P>
