<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Wednesday held talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
the latest developments in the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before leaving Cairo for Gaza, Arafat
said the talks focused on the land handover dispute between the
Palestinians and Israel, which has delayed for the last two weeks
Israeli troops withdrawal from another 5 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side proposed some changes for the maps of
withdrawal submitted by Israel, but Israel has failed to respond,
Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of trying to avoid giving a reply.
</P>
<P>
Prior to each of the previous withdrawals, the two sides would
give their own suggestions and demands and sign the maps after
discussions, Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
But this time, Israel decided the areas itself without
consulting with the Palestinians, he said, stressing that it is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm el-Sheikh Memorandum signed in September, the
withdrawal should take place on November 15. But the Palestinians
rejected the Israeli maps, saying the areas are too thinly
populated and not contiguous.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will visit Washington in the coming few days for talks
with U.S. President Bill Clinton on the latest developments of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations, Palestinian Minister of
Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath said before
leaving Cairo for Paris on a visit.
</P>
<P>
Shaath said he will discuss with French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine ways of advancing the peace process. He added that France
is playing a vital role in the process.
</P>
<P>
France has been seeking to play a greater role in the Mideast
peace process, but Israel shows little enthusiasm for France's
participation.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, arrived in Cairo Tuesday, met with Egyptian Prime
Minister Atef Obeid Tuesday night to discuss ways of promoting
bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Obeid said after the meeting that the two sides hoped to
increase the trade volume to 500 million U.S. dollars in the
coming years. 
</P>
