<HEADLINE> Number of HIV Carriers Increases in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of HIV carriers in
Vietnam would increase to between 135,000 and 160,000 by the end
of 2000, of whom 21,000 will develop full-blown AIDS and
10,000-15,000 will die, Vietnam News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Chung A, vice-chairman of Vietnam's National
AIDS Committee, as saying that over the past three years, an
average of 10 HIV cases have been detected and three people have
died of AIDS daily.
</P>
<P>
On the present HIV/AIDS situation, Chung A said that by October
29 this year, Vietnam had detected 16,193 HIV carriers. Of the
figure, 2,907 have developed full-blown AIDS and 1,512 have died.
</P>
<P>
To ease the situation, the committee is devising a HIV/AIDS
control strategy for the 2000-2005 period and will submit it to
the government for approval by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The strategy aims to mobilize the participation of society as
well as assistance from international organizations and foreign
countries in checking the spread of HIV/AIDS among the community
and its harmful effect on the country's socio-economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has made great efforts to control HIV/AIDS in recent
years, Chung A said, adding that all branches, mass organizations
and other social forces have participated in HIV/AIDS prevention.
</P>
<P>
In particular, since early this year
information-education-communication programs on HIV/AIDS have
targeted communes and city wards, thus raising public awareness of
the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
