<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fifteen-Minute Delay for One Third European Flights in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Wednesday that more than one flight in three in Europe have been
delayed over 15 minutes so far this year which caused serious
concerns by the European Union and its 15 member states.
</P>
<P>
Even if some of the delays are due to airports operating at the
limits of their capacity or to the airlines themselves, more than
half are a direct result of Europe's airspace reaching saturation
point, said the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
The economic cost is reckoned to be over 5 billion euros (about
5.25 billion U.S. dollars), while the impact on passengers, though
hard to gauge, is probably the same, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to a study conducted by the EU executive, the main
causes of delay cover four factors:
</P>
<P>
- The steps taken have not been sufficient to cope with the
exponential growth in air traffic;
</P>
<P>
- Air traffic management methods are reaching the limits of
their possibilities;
</P>
<P>
- The organizational structures for air traffic management are
proving ineffective and insufficiently transparent.
</P>
<P>
- The problem is aggravated by the fact that Europe's airspace
is divided between 15 sovereign states which, for various reasons -
above all military - reject any closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a fresh crisis next summer, the European Commission
stressed the urgent need for appropriate technical and operational
measures, calling for more radical action on the underlying cause
of the delays by setting up collective management of Europe's
airspace.
</P>
<P>
"Europe cannot keep the frontiers in the sky that it has
managed to eliminate on the ground," the Commission said.
</P>
<P>
Now the European Union is determined to tackle the severe
delays that have built up in recent years and calls for a major
political move by all member states. The 15-nation European bloc
wants to see in the future "a single European sky". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Officials Ask Australians to Undergo Drugs Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 1 (Xinhua) -- French government officials,
based on their new anti-doping powers, on Wednesday demanded that
Australian tennis players take a drugs test just 48 hours before
the start of the Davis Cup final in the southern French city of
Nice.
</P>
<P>
Unaware of current French law, Australian captain John Newcombe
initially asked for clarification, but finally agreed to allow his
players to be tested.
</P>
<P>
The International Tennis Federation appeared not quite familiar
with the regulations passed in November 1998, which allow the
Ministry of Sports to order athletes, including those from abroad,
to be doping tested.
</P>
<P>
Newcombe said he would prefer sports federations, and not
governments, to be responsible for anti-doping control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
