<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Millennium Rites Kicked off Marking Filipinos' Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The lighting of the giant
lantern dubbed "Millennium Filipino" here at the Rizal Park
Wednesday evening hopefully foresees a bright future for the
Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
Everybody gathered at the park to witness the historical event
seemed excited as the lantern was lighted by Philippine President
Joseph Estrada at around 6:30 p.m., as if they were the first to
hear the steps of the highly expected new century and new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
The beautiful songs, in typical Christmas rhythm, flew out the
heart of the naive school children, praying for peace and
prosperity, while youngsters danced for harvest and happiness in
their very national costumes and traditional way.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony which lasted for more than half an
hour, Estrada elaborated the double symbolic meanings of the
Millennium Lantern: Since Christmas is drawing near, it is fitting
that the Yuletide lantern be their beacon in charting a new path
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The lantern that hangs in every home is a mirror of hope and
symbol of light from our Lord Almighty that will guide our path,"
Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
The significance indicated by the countdown clock on the top of
the 30-foot high lantern, however, is obviously far beyond the
forthcoming Christmas.
</P>
<P>
While it is reminding each passer-by the days left before the
coming of the year 2000, it also embodies the Filipinos' longing
for happiness and wealth in the future.
</P>
<P>
The coming of the new millennium, Estrada said, "should serve
as an inspiration to us Filipinos for these signals -- the
worldwide dawning of economic prosperity and hope with the
changing faces in business, commerce and technology."
</P>
<P>
"Here in our country, the new millennium means new challenges
for us to face the problems that come our way," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting the country's culture will enable peoples everywhere
in the world to see the real Philippine picture, while science and
technology will transform the nation's industries for the benefit
of the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the majority of the Filipinos, especially the
disadvantaged sector in the rural areas, are farmers, the
president said all these developments will depend on successful
implementation of their agriculture programs.
</P>
<P>
"If we can unify and enhance these forces, the new millennium
will bring us more opportunities and prosperity," Estrada
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Secretary Cemma Cruz-Araneta, who chairs the Committee
on the Turn-of-the-Century Celebration, also said the Millennium
Filipino marker symbolizes hopes and joy in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Turn-of-the-Century Committee is part of the Presidential
Commission on the New Century and the Millennium, now headed by
Agriculture Secretary Edgardo Angara.
</P>
<P>
The New Century Commission was set up by President Estrada in
July in a bid to plan and oversee all activities aimed at greeting
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The millennium celebration will be further highlighted in
activities in the week starting from December 26 and culminate on
the New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
According Angara, a "Millennium Village" will also rise at the
Rizal Park, where agricultural products and achievements in arts,
culture, science and technology, along with indigenous and
adaptive handicrafts and tropical flora, will be exhibited.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here warmly lauded the marriage between agriculture
and tourism, saying the villagers will be encouraged to use
"cultural marketing" in selling their products.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in October, the government also declared the production
of special edition stamps, bills and coins to commemorate the
country's celebration of the coming of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Angara said this activity aims to give a lasting legacy for the
new generation by depicting in the commemorative items the
government's pro-poor initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that if the government sticks to carrying out
its pro-poor plans, including agriculture modernization, the food
security program, the affordable mass housing project and more
educational access to children in poor rural areas, the country
will be sure on the right way to poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Others said the president's emphasis on promoting agriculture,
science and technology and culture gives them a new hope that
their country will be propelled into more prosperity in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
These lovely hopes have not only blossomed in the fireworks
skyrocketing at the end of the ceremony, but also in the heart of
the friendly and good-willed Filipinos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
