<HEADLINE> U.N. Publishes Trade-Related Environmental Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) Thursday released six reports that show how
countries can take actions to address trade-related environmental
degradation.
</P>
<P>
"These reports clearly demonstrate how individual countries can
identify the impacts of recent trade liberalization on their
natural and environmental resources, and then develop innovative
strategies to address negative impacts and strengthen positive
ones," UNEP Executive Director Klaus Toepfer said at the launch of
the reports which coincided with the Third World Trade
Organization ministerial meeting in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
The reports include new action-oriented research on
trade-related environmental problems in the forestry, mining,
fisheries, manufacturing and water sectors, the spokesman of
Nairobi-based UNEP Tore Brevik said.
</P>
<P>
Each report concludes by recommending a set of practical
measures that promise to effectively halt trade-related
environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The six reports cover following countries of Bangladesh, Chile,
India, the Philippines, Romania and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
today's diplomatic news released by Xinhua:
</P>
<P>
Jiang Addresses Int'l Conference on Ozone Layer Protection
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin reiterated China's commitment to
environmental protection and the protection of the ozone layer at
an international conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are gathering here to explore concrete ways of protecting
the earth," which is something that is of great importance, Jiang
said at the opening ceremony of the High-Level Segment of the 5th
Meeting of the Parties to the Vienna Convention and the 11th
Meeting of the Parties to the Montreal Protocol.
</P>
<P>
He extended his heartfelt congratulations to the convening of
the meeting and a warm welcome to all the delegates and guests who
came from different parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese President Meets Iranian Vice-President
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin met with Iranian Vice-President
Mohammad Hashemi here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that China and Iran are ancient civilizations with a
long standing friendship between them. Sino-Iranian bilateral
relations have had sustainable development in recent years, Jiang
added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government treasures its ties with Iran and values
Iran's role in international and regional affairs, Jiang noted,
adding that China will continue to promote and foster bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
CPPCC Chairman Leaves For Visit to Three Asian Countries
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), left here
today to pay an official goodwill visit to Sri Lanka, Maldives,
and Japan at the invitation of the governments of the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Seeing Li off at the Great Hall of the People this morning were
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, CPPCC Vice-Chairman Chen Junsheng and
Deputy Director of the General Office of The Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee Hu Guangbao, and the three countries'
diplomatic envoys in Beijing.
</P>
