<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Returned Students Contribute to Shanghai's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Over the past 20 years, more
than 17,000 Chinese students studying abroad have returned to the
country's largest city, Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents one-sixth for all returned Chinese
students, according to a local educational official.
</P>
<P>
Now, there are a total of 80,000 Shanghai people studying
abroad. Most of those who have returned are professional personnel,
73 percent are back from developing countries, and 72 percent have
got master's degrees or Ph.D.s, the official said.
</P>
<P>
They are playing an important role in promoting the city's
economic and social development. Some 69 returned scientists have
become academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and
the Chinese Academy of Engineering, 1,192 are tutors of doctoral
students, and 2,980 are in charge of state key research projects.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the returned scholars are under age 40,
the "golden age" for scientific research, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branch of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
has sent many people to study overseas, and most have returned to
the motherland to assist in its social and economic development,
he said.
</P>
<P>
A large portion of them have contributed significantly to the
city's economic construction and scientific research, especially
in some new fields such as new materials, international finance
and computer science, he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the returned students have set up 750 high-tech
and industrial enterprises in Shanghai, involving nearly 200
million US dollars of investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
