<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loans to Mongolia, Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Thursday a 25 million U.S. dollar loan to Mongolia for
the country to reform its public sector through the Governance
Reform Program.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release of the ADB, the program will
overhaul the public sector's financial and administrative
machinery and bring in institutional mechanisms to increase
efficiency, transparency, accountability and predictability.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian government has a 10-year plan to reform the
public sector of which the Governance Reform Program is a 30-month
pilot phase.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan, coming from its concessionary Asian Development
Fund, will have a maturity of 24 years, including a grace period
of 8 years.
</P>
<P>
The rate of interest will be one percent per annum during the
grace period and 1.5 percent thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, the ADB agreed to provide an emergency loan
of 5 million dollars for Tajikistan to rehabilitate infrastructure
which was badly-damaged by floods and landslide earlier this year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
