<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BNR Governor Slams IMF's Policy on Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Romanian National Bank (BNR)
Governor Mugur Isarescu slammed Thursday the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) for making public the amount of Romania's
private loans, as a precondition for the payment of the second
tranche of a stand-by loan approved by the organization last
August.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announcement that Romania needed to draw 100 million U.
S. dollars from international private capital market has created
difficulties for the BNR in attracting loans, since the foreign
banks are regarding Romania as a high-risk country, Isarescu said.
</P>
<P>
Romania's very willingness to contract such high interest rate
loans, which is deemed a confirmation that the country is in
financial trouble, further prompted suspicion on the international
private capital market, said the BNR chief.
</P>
<P>
Romania successfully passed the repayment peak of its foreign
debt this year and has taken precautionary measures for next
year's repayment of the foreign debt. It at the same time plans to
contract more than 400 million dollars in loans on the
international private capital market.
</P>
<P>
Despite all these efforts, the IMF required Romania to contract
another 100 million dollars from private international lenders, as
a guarantee of its future solvency.
</P>
<P>
Isarescu and Transport Minister Traian Basescu are the only two
Romanian officials to have criticized IMF's policy towards Romania.
Basescu said recently that the IMF was placing Romania in "
formulas drawn up in a laboratory", which are not suitable for
Romania's economic conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
