<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia Free Lebanese Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Israeli South Lebanon
Army (SLA) Thursday released four Lebanese prisoners from its
jail in south Lebanon, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
All four prisoners, detained for collaborating with Lebanese
guerrillas to fight Israeli forces, were freed on humanitarian
reasons, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The freed prisoners were taken by the SLA from its notorious
Khiam jail to their homes inside the Israeli occupied border zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a so-called security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's resistance movement, spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since been fighting
to oust Israeli forces and its ally SLA.
</P>
<P>
More than 160 Lebanese are still held without trial in the jail
run by the pro-Israeli militia, under Israeli supervision. A
recently released report indicated Israeli complicity in serious
human rights violations in the jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
