<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The second round of the African Pan-Arab exhibition
for Building and Construction (Saie Egypt '99) opened Thursday in
Cairo with the participation of up to 200 foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Most of the foreign exhibitors are eager to open new markets
for their products in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Cairo is simultaneously organizing the first Arab fair for
marble and granite. The two fairs, to last until December 5, were
sponsored by the Egyptian Federation of Building and Construction
Contractors.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The 70th session of the Arab Economic Unity Council
opened here Wednesday under the chairmanship of Libya.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammad Mehdi Salah, Egyptian Minister
of Planning and International Cooperation Ahmed Mahrous el-Darsh
and Egypt's permanent representative to the Council Ahmed Al Darsh
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will endorse an agreement on encouraging and
protecting inter-Arab investments and capital transfer. The
agreement has already been approved by Egypt, Jordan, Sudan, Iraq,
Palestine, Mauritania, Yemen and Libya.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The governments of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
states were urged to diversify and restructure their economies and
to pursue well-studied and successive steps in their economic
reform policies.
</P>
<P>
The GCC Federation of Chambers of Commerce also called upon the
Gulf governments to invest their petroleum revenues in promoting
the ability of GCC states to offset the negative impact on their
economies by the drop in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
It asked GCC states to increase foreign currency reserves,
diversify and develop basic service sectors such as education and
training, to invest more in infrastructure, and to build more
roads and free zones.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government is offering for sale four food
processing plants belonging to the Egyptian Vineyards Company and
six five-star Nile cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
The food processors include a drying plant for dried foods, an
olive oil extracting and preserving plant, both situated in the
old Delta vineyard region of Gianaclis, The Egyptian Gazette
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A drying plant for soft dates and another olive pressing and
preserving plant in the northwestern province of Mersa Matruh are
also for sale.
</P>
<P>
The six Nile cruise ships, working on the Luxor-Aswan line, are
all five-star but of various capacities, said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
