<HEADLINE> More Refugees Expected to Reach Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Despite developments in
the peace process in both Burundi and the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) , the influxes of refugees to Tanzania are likely
to continue, a UN report said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report issued by the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), from January to November 1999,
a total of 75,358 Congolese and 43,874 Burundian refugees arrived
in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Burundi were particularly high in October and
November due to the prevailing insecurity.
</P>
<P>
After over 35 years of providing refuge to those fleeing from
crisis in the Great Lakes Region and other countries in Africa,
Tanzania currently hosts 399,474 refugees from the neighboring
countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Refugees predominantly from Burundi (289,843), the DRC
(97,401), Rwanda (7,707) and Somalia (3,300) are now staying in 12
designated locations in the country's northern Kagera, western
Kigoma and eastern Tanga regions.
</P>
<P>
With the naming of former South African president Nelson
Mandela as the new facilitator in Burundi peace talks, it is hoped
that repatriation of refugees to Burundi will resume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
