<HEADLINE> Former Vice-Governor Goes to Jail for Bribery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Meng Qingping, former vice-
governor of Hubei, a central China province, has been sentenced to
ten years in prison for accepting bribes of 140,000 yuan and 100,
000 Hong Kong dollars while he was vice governor of Hainan
Province and later Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Meng was in charge of land use approvals in China's
southernmost province of Hainan between 1989 and 1992, when the
province's real estate sector was booming. Meng was the then vice-
governor of the island province.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate Court in Wuhan has gathered strong evidence
that suggests Meng abused his power by approving land for bribes,
which he said were gifts to his wife and himself.
</P>
<P>
The bribery money has been retrieved by the court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
