<HEADLINE> Russia Threatens to Withdraw From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia threatened Thursday to
consider pulling its troops out of Kosovo if the U.N. mission and
the leadership of the multinational peacekeeping force in the
Yugoslav province do not observe their commitments as stipulated
by the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The threat came after Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov accused the
West of conniving with genocide against non-Albanian residents in
Kosovo, where some 200,000 ethnic minorities have recently fled
the region.
</P>
<P>
Russia "may withdraw its military contingent from Kosovo if
further moves that violate Resolution 1244, which recognizes the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia, are made in
Kosovo," Deputy Foreign Minister Sergei Ordzhonikidze said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3,600 Russian troops stationed in Kosovo as
part of the 40,000-strong multinational force known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has already sent a letter to U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan, urging him "to call head of the U.N. mission in Kosovo
Bernard Kouchner and KFOR Commander Klaus Reinhardt to New York to
give an account of their work," the Interfax news agency quoted
Ordzhonikidze as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Kouchner and Reinhardt must be brought to account for the
killing on connivance and also the disturbances in Kosovo on
November 30 when the so-called Day of the Albanian Flag was marked,
" Ordzhonikidze said.
</P>
<P>
"In front of representatives of the U.N. and KFOR, real
bloodshed and pogroms were unleashed" on that day, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The peacekeeping forces were supposed to have taken effective
measures in advance to prevent this outrage," he added, noting
that the U.N. is likely to discuss the situation in Kosovo in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not make any categorical demands. But we would
like to hear clear-cut explanations of the developments in Kosovo,
" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
