<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspapers Auction New Year's Day Ad Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Nine influential Chinese
newspapers Wednesday auctioned advertisement space in the issues
to be published on New Year's Day of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The papers are People's Daily, the overseas edition of People's
Daily, China Daily, China Securities News, Financial News, China
Business Times, Beijing Evening News, Hong Kong's Wen Wei Po and
Macao Daily News.
</P>
<P>
The auction, the first of its kind in the country, raked in
total sales of 5.05 million yuan. The base price for all of two
dozen pages for sale was more than seven million yuan.
</P>
<P>
China Guardian Auctions Co., Ltd., a leading auction house in
the country, sponsored the event.
</P>
<P>
Kou Qin, vice president of the auction company, called it an
important experiment for local newspapers in transition to a
market economy system. The ads of the first day of 2000 are of
high commercial value, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The auction has caught the attention of other newspapers. China
Youth Journal commented that the Chinese media, especially the
leading papers, are facing increasingly fierce competition in
advertising and that Wednesday's auction was a good idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
