<HEADLINE> Pakistani Chief Executive to Visit Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Chief Executive
General Pervez Musharraf will pay an official visit to Iran in the
very near future, said Pakistani ambassador Javid Hussain on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government of Pakistan attaches "the highest level of
importance" to its relations with Iran, the ambassador said,
quoted by the official Islamic Republic News Agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Musharraf, after assuming power in Pakistan last
October following a military coup which ousted former Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, has expressed his desire and the desire of
Pakistani people for closer ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
So Musharraf's visit to Iran "will be in a very near future,"
the ambassador said, "I am sure we will have this important visit
from the Pakistan side at the level of the Chief Executive to Iran
at a certainly very near future."
</P>
<P>
He said the visit would provide an opportunity for leaders of
the two countries to exchange views on important bilateral issues,
on how to strengthen bilateral cooperation, on regional issues, so
that the two countries can adopt a common approach to those
regional issues particularly the issue of promoting peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Islamabad-Tehran relations are deeply rooted in "our
history, in our cultural affinity and geographical proximity and
common strategic interests and in similarity of other national
interests."
</P>
<P>
A Pakistani newspaper reported recently that Musharraf would
visit Tehran in the fasting month of Ramadhan which starts in Iran
at the end of next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
