<HEADLINE> China's PLA Chief Witnesses Thai Military Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chief of General Staff
of China's People's Liberation Army (PLA), Fu Quanyou, witnessed a
military parade here Thursday, which was specially organized to
mark the 72nd birthday of Thai King Bhumibol Adulyadej on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Fu and other military top brass from Australia, New Zealand,
Singapore, Cambodia, the United States and Canada, as well as
Britain's Prince Andrew witnessed the two-hour military parade.
</P>
<P>
After the parade, Fu was invited to a banquet hosted by former
Thai Prime Minister and Defense Minister Chavalit Yoongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
They recalled the healthy development of the relations between
the two armies and exchanged views on issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Fu visited a military academy before
witnessing a mass parachute jumping participated by 572 local and
foreign parachuters.
</P>
<P>
Fu arrived here Wednesday for a five-day official visit, the
first Fu paid to Thailand since he assumed the present post.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, he is expected to call on Crown Prince Maha
Vajiralongkorn after holding talks with Prime Minister and Defense
Minister Chuan Leekpai and Supreme Commander of Royal Thai Armed
Forces, Mongkon Ampornpisit. 
</P>
