<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Chief Urges Political Solution to Chechen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) Ezzidine Laraki on
Thursday called for political solution to the Chechen crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the sidelines of the fifth
Conference of Islamic Information Ministers which opened here on
Wednesday, Laraki expressed concern over the situation in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Russian troops have closed in on the separatist Chechen capital
Grozny in an effort to root out the rebels, who were accused of
intruding into neighboring Dagestan for two times and plotting a
series of apartment bombings across Russia.
</P>
<P>
Laraki said that the OIC has contacted Russian officials to
convey the world Muslims' anxiety toward the bloodshed in Chechnya
and the OIC assistant secretary general would visit Moscow soon to
evaluate the situation.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian military action in Chechnya is an internal
matter, but I think that the Russians should find a political
solution to the crisis," said the OIC chief.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the upcoming visit by an OIC delegation to
Moscow and Chechnya would enable the OIC to present specified
proposals to the Russian government to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi announced on Wednesday
that he would lead the OIC delegation to Moscow on Monday to
discuss Chechen issue with Russian officials. Iran is now chairman
of the OIC.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi said that the objective of the visit was not
mediating but fact-finding, and his delegation has no plan on
mediation.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov informed Kharrazi on
Monday night that Russian cabinet had accepted the proposal by
Kharrazi on a visit by an Iran-led Islamic delegation to Moscow
for talks on the Chechen issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
