<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One More Market Boat Begins Services in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- One more market boat carrying
749 tons of goods began its sale trip Wednesday from here to
Mandalay, Myanmar's second largest city, to conduct trading at
towns and villages along the country's Ayeyawaddy River.
</P>
<P>
The aim of such services is to promote goods exchange between
northern and southern parts of the country and bring about
convenience for people on the river banks to buy goods at
reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
The "Myathida" market boat, which departed from the Yangon
Nanthida Port, is made up of 33 shops and booths of ministries of
industry, cooperatives and agriculture and irrigation as well as
some private shops and will sell products from these ministries,
according to sources at the Ministry of Transport Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Goods such as beverages, textile and clothing, ceramics and
chemical products, farm machinery, cycles, power-tillers and
consumers goods are on sale on board the ship, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Ministry of Transport has been extending its
passenger and freight transport services with the Inland Water
Transport stretching out more operations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of commuter market boats between Yangon
and Mandalay and between Mandalay and Bhamo, the northernmost part
of the country, has also been extended, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Earning within the eight months from April to November this
year reached 914 million Kyats (3 million U.S. dollars), the
sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has been operating such kind of boat sale services
since January 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
