<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Dismisses Burundi Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has dismissed accusations that his government
allows refugees in the country to train, equip and launch attacks
on Burundi, the Daily News newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Wednesday that his government is "fed up with
endless but baseless accusations that we allow refugees in
Tanzania to attack Burundi", and "that has never been our policy".
</P>
<P>
The strained relationship between the two countries came to
boil in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha Wednesday when Mkapa
was speaking at the opening session of the Eighth Great Lakes
Summit on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The recent escalation of violence in Burundi after the death of
the late chief mediator Julius Nyerere had sparked a refugee
influx into Tanzania, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The influx of refugees into Tanzania has more than doubled.
With already more than 800,000 refugees, Tanzania finds it
difficult to cope with this new development," said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
"We earnestly ask those countries that generate refugees to get
their act together quickly, taking advantage the tremendous
support for peaceful negotiations that the region is ready to
offer, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president further urged the countries to "create
that political dispensation and those security guarantees that
will stop their citizens from looking for sanctuary and succor in
other countries."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Tanzania was the most interested in seeing
that the conflict in Burundi be resolved quickly and successfully,
and that the tiny central African country becomes democratic,
stable and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
"This ultimate goal can only be agreed upon by the Burundians
themselves and should not be imposed upon them," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to be the scapegoat for procrastination in the
negotiations, and we abhor even the perception that Tanzania is an
obstacle to the speedy resolution of the Burundi conflict," Mkapa
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some diplomats say that ties between Tanzania and
Burundi are so strained that the two countries are on the verge of
becoming hostile to one another.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts also observe that Tanzania is likely to be sucked
in the war within Burundi if the relations between the two nations
do not improve in the foreseeable future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
