<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Urged to Take AIDS Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's National AIDS
Advisory Council has urged Tanzanians to voluntarily screen
themselves against AIDS disease as a way to prevent the spread of
the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
It is high time every responsible citizen knows his health
status as far as HIV is concerned, chairman of the AIDS advisory
council and former Tanzanian President Ali Hassan Mwinyi told the
nation in the World AIDS Day commemoration in Dar es Salaam
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi said voluntary screening will help people keep a
watchful eye on their health status and allow the government to
draw strategies on how to combat the disease.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health in collaboration with other institutions
has already made arrangements to ensure that such exercise be
carried on smoothly, he revealed.
</P>
<P>
The former president challenged all Tanzanians to desist from
promiscuous sexual life that causes 80 percent of AIDS infections.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi also urged parents to be more open in talks with
children to prevent them from becoming victims of the killer
disease.
</P>
<P>
He warned that failure to prevent the spread of the AIDS
disease will erode the cherished peace, tranquility and solidarity
in the country.
</P>
<P>
"A household with a patient does not enjoy any peace nor does a
nation with many AIDS patients," he added.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics say that by the end of last year, a total
of 550, 000 AIDS cases had been reported in Tanzania and there
were 1.6 million HIV- positive people while there were 400,000
orphans whose parents died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
