<HEADLINE> Zambia Exports More in COMESA Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's annual export to other
member countries of the Common Market for East and Southern Africa
(COMESA) increased to 228 million U.S. dollars last year compared
with 69 million dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's total annual trade volume in intra-COMESA market rose
to 384 million dollars from 205 million dollars during the same
period last year, according to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Thursday quoted Zambia Association of
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI) chief economist Ernest
Mwape as saying that with the coming of the Free Trade Area
arrangement one year away local goods will have a greater chance
of penetrating into the regional market.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from all the other likely benefits, Zambia manufactured
products will also stand a better chance of gaining outside
markets. This is good for us," he said.
</P>
<P>
But some Zambian business leaders have warned that the
country's poor competitive edge over major trading partners will
further worsen its weak agricultural and industrial bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
