<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Resume Aid to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
decided to resume the suspended 439-million-U.S. dollars financial
aid to Nigeria following improved human rights records in the
country, EU office in Lagos has said.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a statement that officials of the union
would soon visit the west African country to facilitate the
resumption of the aid, the Guardian newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement lauded the Nigerian government's efforts to boost
the economy in the area of privatization and open market
operations to stimulate foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
With the recent efforts made by the President Olusegun
Obasanjo, EU would continue to assist the government to meet its
needs, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The prevailing circumstances in Nigeria have made it possible
for EU to resume further talks with Abuja in order to strengthen
their closer relations, it added.
</P>
<P>
EU imposed various sanctions, ranging from financial aid to
technical assistance as well as sports, on the most populous
African country during the military regime of the late General
Sani Abacha to protest its human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were relaxed when EU drew up a plan to assist
Nigeria after the inauguration of Obasanjo's civilian government
in May this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
