<HEADLINE> Japan's Mobile Phone Giant Becomes Partner of HK Hutchison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Hutchison Whampoa Limited (
HWL), Motorola Inc. and NTT Mobile Communications Network, Inc. (
NTT DoCoMo) announced Thursday that NTT DoCoMo has agreed to
acquire a 19 percent strategic equity interest in Hutchison
Telephone Company Limited.
</P>
<P>
Motorola also currently holds a 30 Percent equity interest in
the HWL-controlled Hong Kong mobile operator in which NTT DoCoMo
will acquire from HWL a 19 percent interest for a cash
consideration of about 3.175 billion HK dollars (410 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
This transaction places an enterprise value of approximately 20
billion HK dollars (2.6 billion U.S. dollars) on HWL, the largest
mobile operator in Hong Kong with over 1.2 million subscribers
representing a market share of 33 percent, HWL Group Managing
Director Canning Fok told a press conference Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
As part of this transaction, HWL will convert into equity
certain shareholder loans it had made to the company in the past,
Fok said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that HWL's interest in the company will rise from
70 percent to 74 percent as a result of this debt to equity
conversion, resulting in a reduction in Motorola's interest in the
company from 30 percent to 25.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that NTT DoCoMo's technology and vision, combined
with Hutchison's local market presence and Motorola's strength in
mobile communications technology, put Hutchison in an excellent
position to drive the Hong Kong mobile communications industry
forward," Fok said.
</P>
<P>
NTT DoCoMo is currently the largest mobile operator in Japan
with about 27 million subscribers representing a market share of
57 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is in this context that Hutchison, with input from NTT
DoCoMo, plans to expand its portfolio of value-added service
offerings with a view to increasing mobile phone usage for non-
voice applications in Hong Kong, Fok added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
