<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition to Stage New Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's opposition alliance
on Thursday announced a two-day hartal (destructive strike) for
December 5 and 6 to press home its demand for the immediate
resignation of the ruling Awami League-led government to pave way
for early parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first countrywide shutdown since the summit
meeting of the four parties on Tuesday, and the 17th of its kind
this year.
</P>
<P>
The strike call was announced by the major opposition
Bangladesh Nationalist Party, the Jatiya Party, the
Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islamic Oikya Jote (Islamic Solidarity
Front) -- the four components of the alliance -- at different
public rallies in the capital city Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parities also organized processions across the
country Thursday to observe the "Demonstration Day."
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance has been staging a series of campaigns
this year to force the government to resign, calling for early
parliamentary elections which are now scheduled for 2001.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of the four opposition parties met on Tuesday evening
for the first time since the alliance came into being early this
year, vowing to "oust the government" and forming a patriotic and
strong government on a "broad-based unity."
</P>
<P>
Hartal is very common in Bangladesh, where opposition parties
call strikes to oppose the ruling party while the latter adopts
anti-strike activities, often resulting in clashes and causing
heavy economic losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
