<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Urged to Give Priority to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's industry and labor
leaders have suggested the government give priority to poverty
alleviation aided by job creation, the Guardian newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The economic decline of the military rule still persisted and
the only way out is such programs as poverty alleviation, job
creation, infra- structure improvement and adoption of a realistic
fiscal and monetary policies, the leaders said at a workshop in
capital Abuja Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit is staggering at 250 billion naira (2.63 billion
U.S. dollars), or eight percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP) in the first five months of the year, Chairman of the
Nigerian Investment Promotion Commission Kola Daisi said.
</P>
<P>
Worsening poverty situation accentuated by rising unemployment
population and parlous state of infrastructure facilities hindered
the recovery of the economy even after the inauguration of
President Olusegun Obasanjo's civilian government, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge in clashes between communities in Niger Delta is
said to be a direct reflection of a preponderance of unemployed
youths.
</P>
<P>
Lagos-based management consultant, Chief Jusho Ologunde, also
said that not much had been done by the new government to redress
the inherited economic malaise.
</P>
<P>
"The country has not experienced any improvement in standard of
living," he said, adding that a lot of people are crying and
complaining bitterly daily.
</P>
<P>
Executive secretary of Food, Beverage and Tobacco Senior Staff
 Association, Sola Iji, expressed reservation over early recovery
of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the current exchange rate of the naira is
unrealistic and lacks potency in moving the economy forward.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to deregulate fuel prices would aggravate poverty,
 stressing that privatization, as being proposed, would further
alienate a majority of Nigerians from the mainstream of economic
resources, to the advantage of the rich few. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
