<HEADLINE> Philippine Oil Company Attacked with 1 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A security guard was injured
when three unidentified heavily armed men attacked Thursday
morning a gasoline company in Metro Manila by spraying it with
bullets and firing a rifle grenade at it, initial police report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the security guard posted at the Shell
House building in Makati city of Metro Manila was injured when
three armed men fired rifle and grenade at the oil company from a
grey car at about 4:30 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The attack shattered the glass wall above the canopy of the
backdoor of the building, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The security guard suffered injuries in the back because he was
hit with glass splinters. Aside from the security guard, there
were no other casualties.
</P>
<P>
Responding policemen recovered one empty shell of a rifle
grenade and 11 empty bullet shells at the area, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Police probers were still conducting a thorough investigation
of the case to identify the attackers and their motive in
assaulting the office.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has ordered the police to
apprehend the parties responsible for the attack. Several teams
have been dispatched to try to arrest the suspects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, public utilities in Metro Manila were placed under
tight watch following the bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
The public utilities placed in tight watch included gasoline
stations and their offices; water facilities and electrical
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
