<HEADLINE> Greece Police Launch Manhunt for Albanian Bus Hijacker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek police have launched a
manhunt for an Albanian who hijacked a railway bus in northern
Greece early Thursday and escaped with more than nine million
drachmas (about 27,863 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The young Albanian hijacked the Greek bus carrying 49
passengers shortly after it left the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki for the Albanian town of Korce at just before
midnight Wednesday, local police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian, who was armed with a revolver, forced the bus to
reach an isolated farm in Laggina village, west of Thessaloniki,
and robbed the passengers of more than nine million drachmas and
three mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
The entire operation lasted two hours and the hijacker left the
bus at 2:30 a.m. local time and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, two similar incidents took place in northern
Greece, but all the hijackers were killed by police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
