<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israeli Negotiators To Meet on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators are to hold a new round of talks in Ramallah Thursday
in a bid to resolve differences over the maps of Israeli troop
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The two negotiating teams, to be led by Palestinian chief
negotiator Saeb Erekat and his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran, will
discuss issues, among others, related to the transition period as
stipulated in the Sharm el-Sheikh Memorandum signed last
September.
</P>
<P>
The issues include opening of a northern safe passage between
Gaza and the West Bank and release of the third group of
Palestinian prisoners from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sharm el-Sheikh Memorandum, the two sides should
reach a framework agreement on final-status by next February and a
final peace treaty by September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The two sides on Wednesday had discussed several economic
issues related to bilateral cooperation within the framework of
the final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israel was scheduled to pull out its troops from 5 percent of
the West Bank territory by last November 15, but differences over
from which areas Israel should withdraw its forces have delayed
the process. 
</P>
