</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Marks Peace Agreement Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- On this day two years ago, the
Bangladeshi government and the tribal rebels signed a historic
document -- the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) peace agreement,
ending the two-decade-long armed conflict in the country's
southeastern hill region.
</P>
<P>
Two years later, the nation is celebrating the treaty's second
anniversary with mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
While the accord has been hailed by many as a "historic event"
and earned Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina the UNESCO peace prize for
ending the insurgency in the three hill districts, it has aroused
mixed reactions among the Bangladeshi people, particularly people
from the hill region.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Awami League is celebrating the occasion, the
opposition is still opposed to it, and tribal leaders have voiced
dissatisfaction over the slow implementation of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Describing the agreement as "a glorious chapter in our national
history" in a message on the eve of the anniversary, the prime
minister said: "It (the agreement) has opened up the opportunities
for peace, stability and development replacing the two-decade-long
bloodshed and war-like situation in the hilly region."
</P>
<P>
She said her government had adopted extensive programs to
implement the CHT under short-, medium- and long-term plans.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Parbatya Chhattagram Jana Sanghati Samity
(Chittagong Hill Tracts People's Solidarity Association, PCJSS)
Shantu Larma, however, has expressed dissatisfaction over the slow
implementation of the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
"This historic peace accord was signed two years ago, but it is
yet to change living condition of the people of the region because
of the slow pace of its implementation," he was quoted as saying
on Wednesday in Bandarban, one of the three hill districts.
</P>
<P>
Larma, who is also chairman of the CHT Regional Council which
was established in May this year in accordance with the peace
accord, also expressed concern over the law and order situation in
the hill districts of Khagrachari, Rangamati and Bandarban.
</P>
<P>
"The civil administration is yet to start functioning
effectively in the region ... There is politicization everywhere
and its bad impact is spreading day by day," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 rebels laid down their arms in early 1998 and
thousands of refugees returned from neighboring India following
the signing of the treaty on December 2, 1997 after a protracted
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
But relations between the government and the PCJSS remain
strained over the procedural delay in carrying out the accord.
</P>
<P>
The CHT Regional Council was formed only in May this year,
nearly one and half years after the signing of the treaty, the
Land Commission which was formed under the agreement to carry out
land survey in the region is not functioning because of the death
of its chairman, and the CHT Treaty Implementation Committee has
not held any meeting since November last year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there have been clashes in the region within the
PCJSS, the political wing of the armed rebels which turned into a
"regional democratic party" early November this year.
</P>
<P>
The PCJSS suffered a split on the issue of the peace accord,
The Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen people have been killed in clashes between the
erstwhile comrades, and at least on one occasion, a home-made bomb
was hurled on the way of a motorcade carrying Shantu Larma to
Rangamati, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
