<HEADLINE> AIDS Takes Toll on Kenyan Military: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's military loses at least
two soldiers every week to the AIDS scourge, Chief of General
Staff Daudi Tonje has said.
</P>
<P>
In his World AIDS Day message to the armed force Wednesday,
Tonje said that the armed forces have recognized the AIDS pandemic
as a military and national disaster and that the military has
"lost very highly trained officers."
</P>
<P>
Tonje told the members of the armed forces to recognize
HIV/AIDS as a personal challenge which does not know rank, social
status or age boundary.
</P>
<P>
As part of its anti-AIDS strategy, the military has a
prevention program, the East African Standard newspaper Thursday
quoted the general as saying.
</P>
<P>
The program includes health education, treatment of sexually
transmitted infections, provision of condoms, HIV/AIDS counseling
services and the care of those infected in all barracks, Tonje
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
