<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE -- The European Union (EU) worked toward seeking broad
support during the third ministerial conference of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Wednesday in an appeal for a comprehensive new
round of global trade talks.
</P>
<P>
Amid massive street protests against global trade
liberalization, representatives from 135 WTO members have gathered
in Seattle in a bid to work out a common ground for the launch of
a new round of global trade negotiations.(US-EU-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
Thursday called for the establishment of a refined all-Asian
regional security structure.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the call at the opening of the Aerospace and
Maritime International Conference held in conjunction with the
ongoing five-day Langkawi International Maritime and Aerospace (
LIMA) '99 exposition in Malaysia's northern resort island of
Langkawi. "In view of the critical importance of keeping peace and
harmony in this area, I would like to call for a refined regional
security structure that will involve every nation in Asia," he
said in his keynote address at the conference. (Malaysia-Asian
Security)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- European Union (EU) members have agreed to cut
short the agenda of the bloc's next inter-governmental meeting in
order to focus on the settlement of problems blocking its eastward
expansion, visiting Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that consensus has been reached on streamlining the
agenda for next year's inter-governmental meeting of the European
bloc in the hope to conclude the meeting by the end of next year
so that the expansion process would not be delayed. Lipponen, who
has already visited most of the EU's 15 members, made the
announcement at a press conference after briefing his Swedish
counterpart Goran Persson on Finland's preparations for the group'
s Helsinki summit next week. (Finland-EU-Agenda)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEATTLE -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Wednesday urged the
developed countries to give the least developed countries greater
access to global markets.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is committed to a comprehensive program to
help the poorest nations become full partners in the world trading
system," he told the trade ministers attending the third
ministerial conference of the World Trade Organization (WTO) here.
Clinton said he is working on this initiative with the European
Union, Japan and Canada and "we have to do more." (US-WTO-Meeting)
</P>
</TEXT>
