<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets Tanzanian Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao met today with visiting Tanzanian Minister of Defense and
National Service Edgar Maokola-Majogo.
</P>
<P>
Hu, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission (CMC),
said that the Chinese government has always attached importance to
friendly ties with Tanzania and other African nations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin recently wrote to leaders of
African countries calling for the convocation of the "China-Africa
Cooperation Forum -- Ministerial-Level Conference in Beijing in
2000", a move that has shown China's sincere hope and unremitting
effort not only to strengthen its friendly ties with African
countries, but also to promote solidarity and cooperation among
developing countries, said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hu lamented over the death of the former Tanzanian President
Nyerere, and voiced the hope that the traditional friendship and
comprehensive ties between China and Tanzania, forged by both
leaders of the elder generation, will score better development in
the coming century.
</P>
<P>
Hu also thanked the Tanzanian government for supporting China
on the issues of Taiwan, Tibet and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Majogo replied that Tanzania will treasure the friendship
between both countries, adding that Tanzania highly appreciates
China's role in international affairs and its effort in
maintaining world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Tanzania will continue to hold unswervingly
to the "One-China" policy.
</P>
<P>
CMC Vice-Chairman Chi Haotian, also state councilor and defense
minister, attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
