<HEADLINE> Kenya to Drive out Somali Factionalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has ordered members of warring Somali factions resident in
Kenya to return to their homeland, the Daily Nation newspapers
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president said that his government would not allow any
threat to the country's security and peace, adding that the
security of Kenyans is above anything else.
</P>
<P>
Moi made the remarks at the Kenyatta International Airport in
the capital Nairobi Wednesday upon returning from a three-day
official visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, Moi together with his
Tanzanian counterpart Benjamin Mpaka and Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni signed the treaty establishing the East African Community
and attended the 8th Great Lakes regional summit on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan president expressed concern that refugee flocking
into Kenya had brought firearms which had been used to cause
increased insecurity in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Moi also urged district commissioners, leaders and security
officers at border areas to beef up security and wipe out cattle
rustling which has caused deaths among innocent Kenyans. 
</P>
