BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- China's four asset management
corporations today signed a framework agreement with the China No.
1 Automotive Group and 10 subsidiaries of the Shanghai Electronics
(Group) Company, involving a debt of 12.45 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China began to implement debt-to-equity swap plan since the
beginning of the fourth quarter, aiming to minimize financial
risks and cut debt burden of State-owned enterprises by swapping
non-performing loans of banks to their equity in enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed today, the four AMCs led by
the China Huarong AMC and the China Development Bank will jointly
organize new limited companies together with the 11 enterprises,
and Huarong will become a major shareholder of the new companies
by holding shares worth 3.2 billion yuan in No.1 Automotive Group
and shares worth 3.45 billion yuan in the 10 companies under the
Shanghai Electronics Group.
</P>
<P>
The other three AMCs and the CDB will also hold shares in these
new companies.
</P>
<P>
After the implementation of the swap plan, the asset to
liability rate of these enterprises will be lowered by an average
of 25 percent, enabling them to improve developing momentum and
competitiveness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
