<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genghis Khan's Offspring Face New Challenges In the New Millennium (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, December 2 (Xinhua) -- For Zhaorigetu, a 26 year old
Mongolian, his biggest dream is to become a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
Zhaorigetu lives in a house made of bricks and tiles, instead
of roaming on horseback like his ancestors. His place of birth,
the Banner of Hexigten of Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, was
the hereditary estate of Genghis Khan's father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
Bloodlines link the young Mongol with the family of Genghis
Khan. An oxhide portrait of Genghis Khan (1167-1227) hangs on the
wall in his house. Yet he knows little about the Great Khan except
that the Mongolian hero had led a military expedition as far as to
the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
Zhaorigetu is busy everyday taking care of his 200-hectare
grasslands and 300 sheep. With an annual income of 80,000 yuan (
nearly 10,000 U.S. dollars), he is much richer than many urban Han
Chinese residents. The average annual income for an urban resident
last year was about 650 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Not all Mongolians share Zhaorigetu's dream of striking it rich.
Gurizhabu, for instance, is a 38th generation offspring of Borshu,
a brave general of Genghis Khan. He still looks after the
Mausoleum of Genghis Khan in the Il Yu League which was built in
1956.
</P>
<P>
"This is a holy mission that must be passed on from generation
to generation," the 58-year-old Gurizhabu said. However, according
to Bilige, his eldest son, taking care of the mausoleum is not
only a mission but "a way of making a living". Bilige receives 500
to 600 yuan (about 60 to 72 U.S. dollars) a month for looking
after the Mausoleum. His dream is to become an actor or go to
college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
