<HEADLINE> Namibia Begins Votes Counting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's presidential and
 parliamentary elections had been completed without violence and
the first results are due by 11 a.m. Thursday, according to
information from Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
"We can say the polling process was successful," Peter
Mietzner, spokesman for the Namibian electoral commission was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ballot boxes, kept in police custody after polling stations
closed at 9 p.m. Wednesday, were taken to counting centers in the
country's 103 constituencies. The counting of votes begun at 8
a.m Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on some complaints about opposition officials not
having been allowed into polling stations, or being treated less
than courteously, electoral officials said there had been no
reports of violence or intimidation.
</P>
<P>
However, the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance (DTA) and the
newly-formed Congress of Democrats, both official opposition
parties, said they had not agreed but had decided to bide their
time and "see how things go from here".
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
