<HEADLINE> Genghis Khan's Offspring Face New Challenges In the New Millennium (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Today, the Great Khan's offspring have a radio and television.
Many villagers also have telephones.
</P>
<P>
Chaobatur, a curator at the Ordos Museum, said that Mongolians
will certainly have a more comfortable life in the next century. "
Even girls in the countryside prefer to wear jeans instead of
traditional ethnic clothes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining traditions, national identity and language will be
a challenging task in the next century. With the help of the
central and local governments, many Mongolians are currently
working to ensure that traditions are not destroyed amidst
economic development.
</P>
<P>
"By melding the past with the present, the offspring of Genghis
Khan will have no regrets in making new achievements," said
historian Qizhongyi, 72, the 34th linear descendent of Genghis
Khan. "Our dream will never fade because we have inherited the
iron will spirit of Genghis Khan and his infinite wisdom."
</P>
