<HEADLINE> More Relief Food to Drought-hit Northwest Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
increased its monthly relief food to Turkana District in
northwestern Kenya from 6,000 bags (90 kgs per bag) to 7,000 bags
of maize and 175 bags of beans.
</P>
<P>
Turkana District Commissioner Alloys Otieno disclosed this
Wednesday at a meeting to assess the famine situation in the
district.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 people have died in Kokuro and Meiyan areas in
Turkana as the drought situation in the district is worsening, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday. .
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people are threatened with imminent death unless
urgent relief supplies are delivered to the starving in northern
parts of Turkana District, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kenyan government has allocated 268 million
shillings (about 3.6 million U.S. dollars) to the National Cereals
and Produce Board for purchasing maize for relief supplies in the
famine-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
A number of non-governmental organizations in Kenya have also
joined in the relief service by carrying out blanket and food
distribution in the arid district bordering Ethiopia and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Otieno admitted that there was a hitch in transportation of
relief supplies as most transporters were unwilling to go the
affected areas due to bad roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
