<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boom in U.S. Steam Coal Demand Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. steam coal demand will
grow during the next 10 to 15 years, surpassing 1.2 billion tons
around 2010 under existing environmental rules, said a report
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the report from U.S. management
consulting firm Hill &AMP; Associates, coal's growth is not as fast as
the overall demand for electricity, and coal's share of generation
therefore falls somewhat even as the tonnage continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, new ozone and fine particle rules proposed by the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency form a caveat, the report said.
Should those rules take effect, coal use would be restricted by 70
million to 80 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The industrial market for coal will continue to fade, said the
report, forecasting that the future will see more industrial
companies switch to natural gas for environmental reasons.
</P>
<P>
Domestic coal producers will continue their struggle to tap
into overseas markets. But the report said that the U.S. steam
coal exports will continue to decline as foreign coal producers
continue to cut their costs at a rate faster than U.S. producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
