<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Common Tariff May Help End GCC-EU Aluminium Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The latest move by Gulf Arab
countries toward establishing a customs union could help end an
aluminium tax row between the European Union (EU) and the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC).
</P>
<P>
At their annual summit in Riyadh last Sunday, GCC leaders
agreed to a common customs tariff of 5.5-7.5 percent and decided
to establish the long-awaited customs union by March 2005.
</P>
<P>
This initiative could lead to some give-and-take on the part of
both the EU and the GCC on the aluminium issue, which involves
Europe's 6 percent duty on primary aluminium imports from the
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The GCC and the EU may find a mutually agreeable solution even
before the actual creation of the GCC customs union by 2005, said
Gert Adomeit, who heads the German Industry and Commerce Office in
the United Arab Emirates (UAE), quoted by the Gulf News newspaper
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The EU currently imposes a blanket 6 percent duty on all
aluminium imports from the GCC, which comprises the UAE, Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Being the leading Gulf exporters of aluminum to the EU, the UAE
and Bahrain are the worst affected by the duty.
</P>
<P>
A recent foreign ministerial level meeting of the GCC and the
EU failed to resolve the issue. And the UAE is currently leading a
coalition against the tariff at the on-going ministerial
conference of the World Trade Organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
Aluminium formed the major component of UAE's 1998 exports to
Germany, which amounted to 660.6 million dirhams (about 180.5
million U.S. dollars). Other exports included textiles and crude
oil.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, Germany exported 6.97 billion dirhams (about
1.9 billion dollars) worth of goods to the UAE, with cars and
trucks accounting for a third of the total. Chemicals and
pharmaceutical products formed the other major export categories.
</P>
<P>
The UAE-Germany trade volume for 1999 is expected to rise by
over 5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
