<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
news items in leading Turkish newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Russia has reduced its natural gas supplies to pressure
Ukraine to repay its debts to Russia and this has caused the
problem of gas shortage in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma has asked his Turkish
counterpart Suleyman Demirel to help negotiate a solution to the
row with Russia.
</P>
<P>
In order to solve the power shortage problem, Turkey started to
use diesel oil in power plants in some areas. The Energy Ministry
also decided to double the amount of electricity imported from
neighboring Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Cumhuriyet (Republic):
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign Ministry spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that it was
not right to link the Helsinki summit of the European Union (EU)
with the Turko-Greek problems.
</P>
<P>
"Our expectations and hope are that Turkey's candidacy is
officially confirmed in Helsinki. This is our demand, not what
Greece says," said the spokesman at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- The partners of Turkish coalition government held an
emergency meeting late Monday to discuss the suspension of
execution against outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party leader Abdullah
Ocalan as requested by the European Court of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
It seems that they have reached a consensus to wait until the
European Court makes a final decision concerning Ocalan's case.
</P>
<P>
The agreement might be shaky, however, as several members of
Deputy Prime Minister Devlet Bahceli's Nationalist Action Party
and Tansu Ciller's True Path Party are pressing for the immediate
execution of Ocalan's death sentence. 
</P>
