<HEADLINE> U.N. to Grant Thai King TeleFood Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations (U.N.) will present the
TeleFood Medal to King of Thailand Bhumibol Adulyadej on his
birthday on December 5 in recognition of his efforts for rural
people.
</P>
<P>
The medal, the first since the TeleFood project was established
by the U.N. agency three years ago, is being awarded for the
king's contribution to food security through the initiation of
more than 100 agricultural and irrigation projects, a press
release of the Public Relations Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the front side of the bronze medal is a portrait of the
king, wearing his usual inspection outfit and with a camera and a
pencil in his hands.
</P>
<P>
On the reverse side are four pictures of Thai farmers from four
sectors -- fruit and vegetables, rice, household livestock and
fishery. The pictures are circled with the legend "Food Security
in Recognition of Invaluable Support of Telefood."
</P>
<P>
The design demonstrates the king's new farming theory, which
advocates an integrated approach and self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
The TeleFood project was set up at the 1996 World Food summit
in Rome, Italy. The event brought together 176 member countries to
join forces in a bid to reduce the number of hungry people by half
from 800 million by 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
