<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Allows Some Palestinian Refugees Back to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel will allow several
thousand Palestinian refugees to return to the Palestinian
self-rule areas in the Gaza Strip, the Ha'aretz newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Israeli security sources as saying that the
move was made under an old agreement, which dealt specially with a
refugee camp in the town of Rafah on the Israeli-Egyptian border.
</P>
<P>
During the 1967 Middle East war, many Palestinian refugees were
forced to leave their homes and they built the Rafah refugee camp
along the Israeli-Egyptian border.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing of the Camp David agreement between
Israel and Egypt in 1978, the camp was split into two and
thousands of refugees remained in the area.
</P>
<P>
According to a refugee return plan reached by Israel, the
Palestinians and Egypt shortly after the Oslo accord in 1993, 640
Palestinian households were permitted to return and make their
homes again in the Gaza Strip till the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on Tuesday in Gaza, Israel, Egypt and the
Palestinians agreed to accelerate the return of those refugees.
</P>
<P>
However, the newspaper reports said, the permit of these
refugees' return is a single case and has nothing to do with the
debate over the right of return of Palestinian refugees or the
absorption of refugees in the Palestinian National Authority
territory.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Monday that Israel will
not allow "a single Palestinian refugee" to return to Israel and the
Palestinian autonomous areas.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Palestinians were displaced and forced to find
shelters in neighboring Arab countries in the Arab-Israeli
conflicts in the past half century. The Palestinians insist that
the refugees have the right to go back to their homeland while
Israel disagrees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
