<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Panda Cub Gets Name at Zoo Ceremony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN DIEGO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A baby panda, the first born
in the Western Hemisphere since 1990, was named Hua Mei, meaning "
China USA", at a ceremony held at the San Diego Zoo Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cub's name was selected and decided by the Chinese State
Forestry Administration after consulting with many other parties
concerned. More than 200 people were present at the ceremony at
the zoo, where the lovely creature was born on August 21, 1999.
According to the Chinese tradition, a baby gets its name on the
100th day after birth.
</P>
<P>
"Hua Mei" in Chinese also means "splendid" and "beautiful."
</P>
<P>
Introducing the baby panda, Chinese consul general in Los
Angeles An Wenbin said that Hua Mei is the youngest Chinese
goodwill ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The name symbolizes the close partnership forged between China
and the United States in the effort to pull pandas back from the
brink of extinction, said Don Lindburg, the zoo's panda team
leader.
</P>
<P>
Hua Mei, now in her fourth month, has gained about 11 pounds
since she was born with a weight of just about four ounces.
During the past months she has been gradually teething,
vocalizing and sitting up by herself. She has got her first
vaccination against canine distemper.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of local volunteers participated in the daily duties of
monitoring the panda baby and her mother. Children have sent them
letters and pictures. In November, four and half million people
from some 40 countries visited the zoo's giant panda Web site,
said Lindburg.
</P>
<P>
Being the first ever to survive past four days in the United
States, Hua Mei has been cared for by her mother since her birth.
Researchers have monitored the two closely, but never intended to
bother them other than to take a weekly health check on the cub,
according to Lindburg.
</P>
<P>
Hua Mei's parents came to the San Diego Zoo in 1996. Under an
agreement between the zoo and China, they would stay here for 12
years. Panda experts in China and the U.S. have been
collaborating year-round on extensive studies conducted at the San
Diego Zoo's Pacific Bell Foundation Giant Panda Research Station
and China's Wolong Giant Panda Research Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Sees Explosive Growth in U.S. Business Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 1 (Xinhua) -- An explosive growth in the
U.S. business Internet access market will be fueled by the demand
for higher bandwidth technologies, according to a report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to grow by nearly 70 percent to an
annual rate of almost 17 billion U.S. dollars in 2003, said the
report from the Strategies Group, a U.S. telecommunications market
research and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
"Small and medium-sized businesses are the growth engine of the
U.S. economy," the report said. "For most of these companies, new
technologies that offer cost-efficient bandwidth will be the only
way to leverage the Internet potential. Technologies like digital
subscriber line have not yet reached widespread adoption, but will
grow tremendously over the next two years."
</P>
<P>
Internet access has become essential for the majority of U.S.
businesses. The report finds Internet penetration increasing in
line with business size: 60 percent of small businesses now have
Internet access, with medium-sized businesses at 80 percent, and
large ones at 90 percent to 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the Strategies Group's forecast, U.S. small
business (with one to 19 employees) Web hosting revenues will
reach 1.67 billion dollars in 1999, 3 billion dollars in 2001 and
3.9 billion dollars in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Narrow Agenda of Next Inter-Governmental Meeting: Finnish PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) members
have agreed to cut short the agenda of the bloc's next inter-
governmental meeting in order to focus on the settlement of
problems blocking its eastward expansion, visiting Finnish Prime
Minister Paavo Lipponen said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that consensus has been reached on streamlining the
agenda for next year's inter-governmental meeting of the European
bloc in the hope to conclude the meeting by the end of next year
so that the expansion process would not be delayed.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, who has already visited most of the EU's 15 members,
made the announcement at a press conference after briefing his
Swedish counterpart Goran Persson on Finland's preparations for
the group's Helsinki summit next week.
</P>
<P>
He said that high on the agenda of the Helsinki summit is to
work out the schedule of the EU's next inter-governmental meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish prime minister expressed his country's hope that EU
members would concentrate on unsettled issues left from the last
summit in Amsterdam: the formation of the Commission of the
European Union, the distribution of voting share among member
countries and the implementation of the majority voting system in
the EU's Council of the Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, whose country currently serves the EU's rotating
president, stressed that the group must solve these problems if it
wants to overcome troubles caused by the upcoming accession of new
members.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Helsinki summit meeting will discuss the EU's
eastward enlargement and hammer out the list of new candidate
countries for the expansion.
</P>
<P>
He added that some EU members hoped the summit would also cover
issues on the bloc's further institutional reform after the inter-
governmental meeting, such as canceling its members' right of veto,
extending the power of the EU parliament, and drafting an EU
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen will travel to Greece on Thursday to wrap up his tour
of EU countries ahead of the EU's Helsinki summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
