<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest Crop of NZ MPs Older, Better Educated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The new crop of MPs elected
last weekend in New Zealand are older and wiser, according to an
analysis by the Wellington-based government and public relations
firm
Saunders and Unsworth.
</P>
<P>
The general election has brought 28 new MPs to the house if its

final results will not change the provisional ones after the
special
votes are counted by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the analysis published Thursday, the average age
of
an MP has risen to 48 years and eight months, up from 47 years in
the
last parliament. Most of the increase resulted from a rise in the
average age of the MPs from the Labor Party, which was the major
winner of last Saturday's election, up to 49 years and six months
from 46 years and six months.
</P>
<P>
The MPs of the new parliament are also better educated with 79
percent of them now having some form of tertiary qualification,
compared with 70 percent in the last parliament.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one percent of the MPs have a university degree, with 33
percent having a master's or honors degree or higher, and 16
percent
of them have a law degree.
</P>
<P>
The most common occupation among the MPs of the new parliament
is
business (14 percent), followed by farmer (12 percent), teacher
(10
percent), local government-public sector (9 percent) and lawyer (8

percent).
</P>
<P>
The number of women MPs has dropped from 35 to 32. 
</P>
</TEXT>
