<HEADLINE> Bryant Says He Will Debut Wednesday Against Warriors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Kobe Bryant, considered one
of the players to take the NBA into the new millennium, announced
his return to action today via the communication avenue of the new
millennium -- his own Web site.
</P>
<P>
"I'm back and ready to go!" the star guard of the Los Angeles
Lakers declared on his Web site, www.kobebryant.com. "I just got
back from the doctor, and he finally gave me the green light to
play (Wednesday night). It's been a long time coming, but
definitely worth the wait."
</P>
<P>
The Lakers host the Golden State Warriors tonight and have made
no official announcement regarding the status of Bryant, who
missed the first 15 games of the season with a broken bone in his
right hand. If Bryant is activated from the injured list before
the game, the Lakers would have to make a roster move.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles is 6-2 in its last eight games and 11-4 this season
without Bryant, who is expected to join Shaquille O'Neal and Glen
Rice in new coach Phil Jackson's triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
Bryant suffered the injury in Los Angeles' first exhibition
game and has missed seven weeks. He was forced to wear a cast to
protect the fractured fourth metacarpal bone in the hand.
</P>
<P>
"How did my injury happen? Well, preseason can be pretty rough
and tumble," Bryant added on his Web site. "Everyone's trying to
establish himself in a new system, and many are just trying to
make the team. Somehow I got elbowed in my hand as I went up for
a rebound. And that's how it was broken, though I didn't know
immediately that it was broken."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the cast was removed and Bryant is putting it up
for bid on eBay, a public auction Web site.
</P>
<P>
Just 21 and in his fourth season directly out of high school,
Bryant played in all 50 games last season and registered 19.9
points, 5.3 rebounds and 3.8 assists per game. He became the
youngest All-Star in NBA history in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
