<HEADLINE> Moldovan Communist Leader Chosen to Form New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Moldovan President Petr
Luchinsky on Wednesday appointed Vladimir Voronin, chairman of the
Moldovan Party of Communists, to form a new government, after
Valeriu Bobutac failed to do so last week.
</P>
<P>
Bobutac had to quit after his cabinet list and policy report
were rejected by the communist-controlled parliament on November
22.
</P>
<P>
Voronin told reporters after accepting the appointment that the
new government would maintain the basic policies of the former
government led by Ion Sturza, with economic development and fight
against crime and corruption as its priorities.
</P>
<P>
Voronin has 15 days to submit his cabinet list and policy
report for parliament approval.
</P>
<P>
He said his party would consult all the parties in parliament
on the issue of naming a cabinet and indicated that his party
might not necessarily take the majority of the cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
President Luchinsky said communist Voronin's appointment does
not mean that Moldova, a former Soviet republic, would return to a
planned economy. Reform and speedy integration with the rest of
Europe remain Moldova's strategic task.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the communists would work with
other parties in parliament to ensure the smooth running of the
new government.
</P>
<P>
Sturza's government resigned on November 8 after failing a
confidence vote in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Voronin's communist party became the most powerful party in
parliament after the collapse of the three-party ruling coalition
following Sturza's resignation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
