<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> . </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar, an agricultural
country, is taking measures and using a step-by-step approach to
turn itself into an agro-based industrial country and has made
achievements to some extent.
</P>
<P>
The country established the Myanmar Industrial Development
Committee in 1995 to formulate industrial policy and provide
guidance for industrialization.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of industrial zones is the second important
measure taken by Myanmar for the expedition of its
industrialization process.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, Myanmar has set up
 18 industrial zones across the country, of which four lie in the
capital city of Yangon and two in Mandalay division in the eastern
part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The third measure is to privatize state-owned industrial
enterprises (SIEs). Myanmar introduced its privatization plan in
January 1995, according to which SIEs are to be transferred to
financially strong and technically manageable private enterprises
for further operation by way of auctioning, leasing and joint
ventures with local and foreign entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The SIEs privatized include those nationalized in the 1960s
when the Myanmar Revolutionary Council government was in power.
</P>
<P>
A major move signifying Myanmar's privatization process is the
leasing out of the largest state-owned Ywama Steel Mill in Yangon
in September 1998 to national entrepreneurs for continued
operation.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 100 SIEs have gone through the privatization
process.
</P>
<P>
The fourth measure is to increase disbursement of loans to
industrial enterprises, fixing the annual interest rate for such
loans as low as 15 percent, only 3 percent higher than that for
saving deposits which is 12 percent. At the same time, it also
cuts the rate of revenues payable by industrial entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there is a total of 53,338
industrial enterprises in Myanmar, of which 1,600 are state-owned,
accounting for 3 percent, while 637 are cooperative-run,
representing 1.2 percent and 51,101 are private-operated, taking
up 95.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The annual output of Myanmar's industrial sector is valued at
over 1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
