<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Said to Be Able to Control AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is able to take
necessary control measures against AIDS as projected as the
country has known the situation on the infection of the disease,
said a high-ranking Myanmar health official.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony here Wednesday marking the World AIDS
Day, Myanmar Health Minister Major-General Ket Sein said, "The
nation is able to control the dreadful disease to a certain
extent," official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The main aim of Myanmar's national AIDS control project is to
disseminate the knowledge on the infection of HIV and AIDS among
the people to enable them to enjoy a healthy life, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister did not disclose the up-to-date number of
 HIV-effected people and AIDS patients in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar launched the anti-AIDS program 10 years ago when a
central committee was formed under the leadership of the National
Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with U.N. agencies such as the World Health
Organization, the U.N. Development Program and the U.N, children's
Fund, local and international non-governmental organizations and
the private sector, Myanmar has successfully carried out these
AIDS control activities with certain success.
</P>
<P>
The annual government fund allocation is about 13 million kyats
(43,000 U.S. dollars) for implementing such programs identified in
the country's National Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics released in 1997, there were
17,846 HIV positive cases and 2,337 AIDS cases in Myanmar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
