<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Invests 14 Million Dollars in China's Port Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Wednesday that it will invest 14
million U.S. dollars to finance the construction and operation of
a new container and general cargo terminal at Zhapu Port in
Zhejiang Province, eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The IFC has signed an agreement for an equity investment of 3
million dollars in China Infrastructure Group Holdings PLC (CIGPLC)
and approved loans totaling 11 million dollars to CIG Zhapu
International Terminal Two Company Limited. The new port will be
built adjacent to an existing petrochemical and general cargo
terminal on the northern half of Hangzhou Bay.
</P>
<P>
The project will mitigate congestion in many of the ports in
this region caused by the growing number of containers, said the
IFC, a member of the World Bank Group.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed, by December 2001, annual design
capacity will be 225,000 twenty-foot units of containers and 600,
000 tons of general cargo.
</P>
<P>
The project supports the government's efforts to improve the
efficiency of port operation in China through increased private
sector participation, said Declan Duff, director of the IFC's
Telecommunications, Transportation, and Utilities Department.
</P>
<P>
The CIGPLC, the flagship company of the China Infrastructure
Group (the Group), is planning to list its shares on the Growth
Enterprise Market of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. The Group is
principally engaged in the development, operation, and management
of infrastructure projects in China, particularly transportation
and logistics.
</P>
<P>
The IFC's investment will be its second port project with the
Group. The IFC earlier made an equity investment of 1.5 million
dollars in CIGPLC and signed a loan agreement to provide 10
million dollars to the Wuhan International Container Trans-
shipment Company Limited, which is a subsidiary of the CIGPLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
