<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Wants Comprehensive New Round of WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) worked
toward seeking broad support during the third ministerial
conference of the World Trade Organization (WTO) on Wednesday in
an appeal for a comprehensive new round of global trade talks.
</P>
<P>
Amid massive street protests against global trade
liberalization, representatives from 135 WTO member countries have
gathered in Seattle in a bid to work out a common ground for the
launch of a new round of global trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Pascal Lamy, EU trade commissioner and head of the EU
delegation, held separate talks with U.S. trade representative
Charlene Barshefsky, trade ministers from Canada, Japan and other
countries, as well as representatives from non-governmental
organizations, in an effort to secure support for the EU stance,
said sources close to the EU delegation.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU circulated a text, which called for the new
round to address a wide range of issues including agriculture,
services, industrial tariffs, anti-dumping, investment and
competition rules -- topics that exist or could potentially arise
during the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The EU also proposes to include non-trade concerns such as
environment and labor in the agenda, which were strongly opposed
by poorer countries fearing wealthier nations would use them as a
new form of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
"We want environmental considerations integrated throughout the
negotiations in the new round," Lamy said, adding that WTO members
should think about where they need to be in not just one or two
years, but 20 years from now.
</P>
<P>
On the link between trade and labor, Lamy said the EU proposal
was carefully designed to be able to avert the possibility of
unfair protectionist sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The EU document has won support from Japan, South Korea,
Switzerland, Hungary and Turkey. But many other WTO members,
including the United States, want a narrower agenda for the trade
talks to be launched by WTO ministers conference starting Tuesday
here.
</P>
<P>
The United States and other leading agricultural producers
intend to keep the focus on the EU's farm subsidies, trying to get
a commitment from the EU to phase out its financial support for
farm products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
