<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Football Association Boss Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- President of the Football
Association of Zambia (FAZ) Teddy Mulonga resigned Wednesday
following a directive from Zambian President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Mulonga has been at loggerheads with the government over the
alleged misuse of the money given to FAZ by the government for
1998 African Cup of Nations in Burkinafaso in which Zambia was
eliminated in the early stages of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
FAZ was given 577 million Kwacha (about 380,000 U.S. dollars at
exchange rate then) for the African Cup finals but failed to
account for the money.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said here Wednesday that he had asked Mulonga to resign.
</P>
<P>
Mulong's exective has been under government squeeze since April
last year when his executive was dissolved by Sports Council of
Zambia (SCZ) over allegations that it had misapplied 577 million
kwacha
</P>
<P>
FIFA, reacting to what it saw as government interference in the
running of soccer, was on the verge of banning Zambia from
international football activities when the government reluctantly
restored in office the FAZ executive led by Mulonga.
</P>
<P>
The government allowed in September in 1998 Mulonga and his
team back in office but it imposed a financial squeeze on the
association in a bid to force the current executive out.
</P>
<P>
In March this year the government said that it was waiting for
a new FAZ executive to be elected before it could once again begin
to provide the financial, moral and logistical support it withdrew
from the FAZ last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
