<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Ethiopia will defend its sovereignty and
territorial integrity despite mounting external pressures imposed
on the country, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency Wednesday quoted Deputy Foreign
Minister Tekeda Alemu as saying that Ethiopians from all corners
believe that the sovereignty of the country should be defended at
all cost. (Ethiopia-Sovereignty)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) on Wednesday
reiterated that the dispute with non-Arab Iran over three
strategic Gulf islands should be resolved through bilateral
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over Abu Musa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs should
be resolved through unconditional bilateral negotiations within a
set time frame, said President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan
on the eve of his country's 28th national day, which falls on
Thursday. (UAE-Islands-Dialog)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations General Assembly Wednesday
urged Israel to resume peace talks with Syria and Lebanon and
withdraw completely from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly Wednesday morning adopted six resolutions,
two of which are on the situation in the Middle East. (UN-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua President Arnold Aleman on Wednesday
announced that his country will impose a 30 percent sovereign tax
on imports from Honduras and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua made the decision to protest the ratification of a
maritime treaty singed between Honduras and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Honduras congress on Tuesday night unanimously ratified the
treaty signed with Colombia in 1986. Honduras also announced it
was moving 2,000 troops to areas near the Nicaraguan border to
prevent timber smuggling. Honduras denied the two moves were
related. (Nicaragua-Taxes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. State Department said Wednesday that
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would be trying to muster
support for a U.N. draft resolution aimed at getting weapons
inspectors into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect that Secretary Albright will have a number of
conversations in the coming days on this resolution, including
with the French foreign minister, the Russian foreign minister,
the British foreign minister and others," spokesman James Rubin
told reporters. (US-UN-Iraq) 
</P>
</TEXT>
