<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Largest Arboretum of Plants for Medicine Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A 24-ha arboretum of plants for
medicinal use, the largest in Asia, is flourishing in the suburbs
of this capital of South China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The arboretum has 2,500 varieties of the plants, 1,000 more
than are recorded in the Ben Cao Gang Mu or Compendium of Materia
Medica, the best-known and respected Chinese medical manual
written by Li Shizhen in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Pu Ruiling, an apothecary and director of the arboretum, said
that the plants are divided into a number of sections according to
their growth characteristics and medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
The arboretum has become a center for growing, breeding,
preservation, research and exchange of medicinal plants. In
addition, it has attracted thousands of domestic and overseas
tourists and experts in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
