<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Launches National AIDS Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Wednesday officially launched the National AIDS Policy to
guide present and future responses to the killer disease in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In the commemoration of the World AIDS Day, Mugabe said it has
taken three and a half years for the government and the Ministry
of Health and Child Welfare to develop the policy through
consultations with the civil society and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
A legislative framework for the establishment of a broadly
based National AIDS Council that would coordinate, promote and
guide an appropriate multi-sectoral response to HIV/AIDS is going
through the parliament, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the task ahead is to ensure that the policy would be
disseminated widely through a medium easily understood by all the
people.
</P>
<P>
The president defended the proposed AIDS levy in the country,
saying this move has won the praise of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The pandemic is not a problem of the Ministry of Health and
Child Welfare and the government alone, he said, stressing
everyone should participate in the fight against the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
It is greatly distressing to note that in spite of having been
exposed to HIV/AIDS education and information, people still
continue to ignore the existence of the infection, Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He called for the expansion and close monitoring of educational
programs in schools to make sure that children and the youth get
much information on the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The president lamented that the premature deaths of young and
middle aged adults are adversely affecting the socio-economic base
of the planned development, further creating challenges for the
nation.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, it is estimated that the total number of
full-blown AIDS cases stands at more than 400,000.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the number of children orphaned through
HIV/AIDS would reach 600,000 by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
