<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Vows to Defend State Sovereignty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will defend its
sovereignty and territorial integrity despite mounting external
pressures imposed on the country, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency Wednesday quoted Deputy Foreign
Minister Tekeda Alemu as saying that Ethiopians from all corners
believe that the sovereignty of the country should be defended at
all cost.
</P>
<P>
He said the principled position of the Ethiopian government is
based on the reality of the country and binding international
conventions.
</P>
<P>
However, Tekeda said, the decisions made by the Security
Council of the United Nations and others with regard to the
Ethio-Eritrean conflict lacked commitment to the international
conventions and failed to condemn aggression.
</P>
<P>
He observed that the Organization of African Unity has been
acting alone to seek a peaceful solution to the conflict based on
the principles of its charter.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been at war since May 1998. Hundreds
of thousands of people were reportedly killed and wounded in the
conflicts. 
</P>
