<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan is hoping that an agreement with Iraq will be
worked out to import petroleum from the oil-rich country in the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Soliman Abu
Alam said that he expected an agreement will be reached during the
ongoing talks with visiting Iraqi Minister of Petroleum Mahir
Rasheed, adding that the Iraqis do not put a ceiling for their
exports to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Gulf war in 1991, Iraq has exported some 80,000
barrels of petroleum per day to Jordan, part of which is paid at
market prices and the rest on preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Olympic Group for Financial Investment made a
gross profit of 108 million Egyptian pounds (31.3 million
U.S. dollars) in April-September, chairman of the group said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Saad Sallam told the Middle East News Economic Service that the
group sold a total of 292.6 million pounds (84.81 million dollars)
worth of products in the first half of its fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The group, which is one of Egypt's largest producers of
electric appliances, is expected to earn a net profit of 40.5
million pounds (11.74 million dollars), Sallam said.
</P>
<P>
The company made 81.5 million pounds (23.62 million dollars) in
net profits in the last fiscal year, he added.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The British Blue Circle Industries (BCI), a producer
of building materials, will buy 73.6 percent of the shares of
Egypt's Alexandria Portland Cement Company, the Egyptian Gazette
newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under a contract signed on Tuesday between the Egyptian
Ministry of Public Enterprise and BCI, the British company will
pay a total of 589 million Egyptian pounds (170.72 million U.S.
dollars) for the purchase, with each share's price amounting to 80
pounds (23.19 dollars).
</P>
<P>
During the year ending on June 30, the Alexandria company sold
189.7 million pounds (54.99 million dollars) worth of cement, made
a pre-tax profit of 82.6 million pounds (23.94 million dollars)
and had net assets of 187.4 million pounds (54.31 million
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
