<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Security Council Calls for More Effective Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Representatives from 38 countries, together with U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan, have voiced their respective opinions on "the
role of the Security Council in the prevention of armed conflict"
at the two-end open debate, which began Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Most of the representatives agreed that the Security Council
should refer to the U.N. Charter and international law as its
guidance in efforts to prevent armed conflicts and work
effectively to address the root cause of armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"There are various kinds of measures that can be taken to
prevent armed conflicts, but there is one general principle all of
them must abide by, that is, actions must be taken in accordance
with the purposes and principles of the Charter of the United
Nations," said Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Delegation maintains that all preventive measures
should only be taken under the prerequisite of respect for the
political independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of
all countries and the will of the government and people of the
country concerned," Qin said. "The principle of non-interference
in internal affairs is the primary principle guiding U.N. actions
in conflict prevention. Preventive measures can only be taken upon
request or with the consent and cooperation by the country
concerned."
</P>
<P>
Qin's statement was echoed by Gennady Gatilov, representative
from the Russian Mission to the United Nations, who said that the
preventive measures "must be done on a voluntary basis, and only
with the unequivocally expressed support of the host country, to
be legal and effective."
</P>
<P>
"Any United Nations action -- including situations with
humanitarian profile -- must be undertaken in accordance with the
Charter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Aboul Gheit, representative of Egypt, said, "
The Security Council must respect territorial integrity and non-
intervention in the internal affairs of States. It must obtain the
approval of States that would be affected by its decisions, before
adopting such measures."
</P>
<P>
Argentina and Brazil also agreed upon the viewpoint. Gelson
Fonseca, Brazilian representative, told the Security Council
debate that "conflict prevention measures must be predicted on the
consent of the Government -- or Governments -- concerned, in full
respect of their sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, the Security Council shoulders the
primary responsibility for the maintenance of world peace and
security. It is also the major institution that the international
community relies on for settling conflict and crisis and realizing
peace.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from such countries as Sudan, Iraq, Namibia and
Belrus also agreed to the observation that nowadays, with
prevention of armed conflict becoming an important means of ending
disputes peacefully, it is only natural that the Security Council
should bear major responsibilities in this area.
</P>
<P>
However, there seems to be a tendency in the current work of
the 15-nation Security Council of putting much emphasis on
intervention while neglecting effective prevention. All too often,
there is heated debate on intervention but no serious study into
the root cause of conflicts is given adequate attention.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that prevention is one of the main tasks of this
Organization," Annan said. "And yet, far too often, we find
ourselves dealing with the effects of conflict rather than its
roots."
</P>
<P>
Fernando Petrella, representative of Argentina, also argued
that the root cause of conflicts must be confronted.
</P>
<P>
Over the decade between 1989 and 1999 alone, there have been
more than 100 armed conflicts in the world, the majority of which
occurred in developing countries. In reality, this is no
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
For too long, the unreasonable old international political and
economic order has seriously hindered the economic development and
social progress of developing countries, putting them at a
disadvantageous position in the new globalization wave.
</P>
<P>
"This is undoubtedly the major cause of the turbulence and
frequent conflicts in some developing countries," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"In the longer term it is even more important to address the
deep-rooted causes of conflicts, which often lies in the social
and economic sphere," Annan said. "Poverty, repressive and
undemocratic government, endemic underdevelopment, weak or non-
existent institutions, political and economic discrimination
between ethnic or religious communities: there are the long-term
causes of many conflicts."
</P>
<P>
"While war is the worst enemy of development, healthy and
balanced development is the best form of long-term conflict
prevention," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Start Agricultural Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Agricultural and Rural
Affairs Minister Husnu Gokalp said on Wednesday that agricultural
reform would be launched in Turkey and the government would
encourage producers.
</P>
<P>
Gokalp said that the reform aims to support producers and
ensure consumers to buy products in good condition. " We will
extend a number of subsidies to farmers," according to a report of
Turkish Daily News.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was committed to fulfilling the criteria of its
agreement with the World Trade Organization (WTO), he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, however, that Turkey should be careful not to
damage its own producers' welfare when importing produce.
</P>
<P>
He said that nobody is opposed to free trade, but we must use
it to our producer's benefit.
</P>
<P>
"Our agricultural producers should be cared for and subsidized
by the government. The big problem Turkish producers face is
finding markets. We must find markets for our producers. The
products must be bought on time, and the money must be paid on
time. In this way we can overcome the problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
All the details of the agricultural reform bill have been
approved by the cabinet, and now it is waiting for
parliament's approval, he disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
