<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: More Effective Prevention of Armed Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the other hand, many representatives said that the Security
Council, which has been playing an important role in conflict
prevention, also has its limits. In fact, it is not a panacea.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, the root cause of the conflicts is the
unreasonable old international political and economic order.
Changes to this situation would only be realized by concerted
efforts by the Security Council, the whole U.N. system and the
entire international community, including regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
Olusegun Apata, representative from Nigeria, said, "The United
Nations' best efforts to resolve conflicts are hindered by the
lack of financial resources, and limited knowledge and familiarity
with the local situations."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Security Council should recognize the importance
of the cooperation between the world body and regional and sub-
regional organizations, such as the Organization of African Unity
and the Economic Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
Martin Andjaba, Namibian permanent representative to the United
Nations, said, "Regional arrangements could contribute to the
maintenance of peace only if their actions are consistent with
Chapter VIII of the Charter."
</P>
<P>
Many representatives called upon the Security Council to be
fair and even-handed in addressing armed conflicts in all areas
worldwide, rather than adopting double standard or on a selective
basis.
</P>
<P>
"Peace in different regions of the world is an indivisible and
related whole. In deliberating the issue of armed conflict
prevention, the Security Council should treat all regions in the
world equally, especially Africa," Qin said. "There should be no
preferential treatment to one and neglect of another."
</P>
<P>
Peter Kasanda, representative of Zambia, said, "Africa
continues to be one of the greatest challenges to the Security
Council, and that would continue to be the case in the foreseeable
future, if the international community fails to assist in
addressing the causes of conflict."
</P>
<P>
Africa has generated more than 8 million refugees, in addition
to millions of internally displaced.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council should give equal treatment to all
conflicts, and should be fair in its execution of its peace and
security responsibilities," he said. "Its authorizing of 6,000
military personnel for Sierra Leone, but 9,100 for East Timor,
made it difficult to escape the perception that a double standard
was being employed."
</P>
<P>
A lot of representatives called for a revision of the tendency
in the United Nations of paying only lip service to Africa, saying
that the world body should put more human and financial resources
to preventive diplomacy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Saeed Hasan, the Iraqi permanent representative to the United
Nations, said, "Due to United States influence in the Security
Council, the Council's credibility had seriously deteriorated over
the past 10 years."
</P>
<P>
"The Council should work for all Member States," he said. "
Decision-making should fully respect the principles and goals of
the U.N. Charter and the General Assembly should fully respect the
principles and responsible for resolutions that violated the
Charter, as well as the Council impassively when it should act."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
