<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Consider Extraditing Former Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will only
consider extraditing former Ethiopian leader Mengistu Haile Mariam
once it receives a formal legal application from Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Essop Pahad, minister in the President's Office, made the
remarks in reply to a question at a news briefing on a cabinet
meeting in Pretoria on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Pahad said as far as he knew no such application had
been made yet.
</P>
<P>
Mengistu came to South Africa from Zimbabwe on November 18 to
receive medical treatment for an undisclosed illness at a private
clinic.
</P>
<P>
He was tried in absentee for crimes against humanity and
genocide which occurred during his 17-year rule from 1974 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
He fled to Zimbabwe in 1991 and has been living there in an
exclusive Harare suburb under heavy protection.
</P>
<P>
According to Pahad, Mengistu came to South Africa for medical
treatment and he would go back to Zimbabwe once the treatment is
completed.
</P>
<P>
South Africa does not have a formal extradition treaty with
Ethiopia and the government could not act on a newspaper report
stating that Ethiopia wanted South Africa to extradite Mengistu,
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, if Ethiopia made a formal request in this regard,
South Africa would consider it, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
