<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Reiterates Dialog As Way to Solve Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) on Wednesday reiterated that the dispute with non-Arab Iran
over three strategic Gulf islands should be resolved through
bilateral dialog.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over Abu Musa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs should
be resolved through unconditional bilateral negotiations within a
set time frame, said President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan
on the eve of his country's 28th national day, which falls on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If dialog fails, the issue should be tackled through
international arbitration, Zayed added.
</P>
<P>
The three islands, located near key shipping lanes in the
Gulf, are claimed by both the UAE and Iran, but have been
controlled by Tehran since 1971, when British forces retreated
from the region.
</P>
<P>
Iran has said that it hopes to solve the "misunderstanding"
through dialog. But the UAE accuses its powerful neighbor of
lacking sincerity.
</P>
<P>
Zayed expressed hope that the tripartite committee established
by the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) last July would devise a
mechanism for the commencement of negotiations between the UAE
and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The committee comprises the foreign ministers of Qatar, Oman
and Saudi Arabia as well as GCC Secretary General Sheikh Jamil
Ibrahim Al Hujailan.
</P>
<P>
"We have great hope that the efforts of this committee will be
rewarded with success," Zayed said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has complained about the slow pace of the committee,
which is expected to submit its first formal report by next June,
when GCC leaders hold a mid-year consultative meeting.
</P>
<P>
The GCC is a region political and economic alliance, grouping
the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
</TEXT>
