<HEADLINE> Panda Cub in San Diego Named Huamei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The female panda cub born on
August 21 in San Diego Zoo has been named Huamei, meaning in
Chinese "China and the America," Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing
announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both the Chinese characters, Hua and Mei, also mean beautiful,
Li explained to reporters at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Huamei's parents, Shishi and Baiyun, have been living in San
Diego Zoo as a 12-year panda reproductive research project between
China's Wildlife Conservation Society and the U.S. Zoological
Society of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
An artificial insemination on Baiyun, the female, has led to
the birth of Huamei, a female panda cub. China's State Forestry
Administration was given the job of finding a name for the cub.
</P>
<P>
"The name of this special panda cub should convey a sense of
joy for the successful partnership of Chinese and American
scientists, a sense of importance of China-U.S. relationship and a
sense of beauty of this marvelous animal," Li told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Huamei is the first giant panda ever born in San Diego, the
first born in the Western Hemisphere since 1990, and the fifth
born on American soil. Previous ones were all born at the National
Zoo in Washington surviving just for a few days.
</P>
<P>
Panda was designed as class-A protected wildlife in 1962 by the
Chinese government. There are more than 1000 giant pandas in the
world.
</P>
<P>
There are only 123 giant pandas living in captivity worldwide,
five of them in the United States including three at San Diego Zoo
and two at Zoo Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
