<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Rises in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction spending
increased 0.3 percent in October to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 699.3 billion dollars, the Commerce Department reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
October's gain followed a revised 0.1 percent decline in total
construction spending in September, far off government
expectations of a 0.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that spending on all government projects led
the increase in total spending, rising a sizable 2.5 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 161.6 billion dollars. Spending
on government housing and redevelopment, schools and other public
buildings all showed gains.
</P>
<P>
Spending on all residential projects also picked up in October,
growing by 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 319.
9 billion dollars. Spending on single-family homes rose by a tiny
amount, while spending on apartment construction fell, reflecting
the impact of rising mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the value of all private construction projects dropped
0.4 percent in October to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 537.
6 billion dollars. Spending on industrial buildings, office
buildings, motels and hotels and educational projects all showed
declines.
</P>
<P>
It marked the fourth consecutive monthly decrease in spending
on private construction projects, something that hasn't happened
since March-June 1995.
</P>
<P>
Builders in some parts of the country have experienced
shortages of skilled workers and some building materials, which
can delay or disrupt construction schedules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
