<HEADLINE> Kenya Banking Sector to Recover Next Year: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Central Bank Governor
Micah Cheserem Wednesday predicted that the flagging banking
sector in the country will recover next year.
</P>
<P>
"The scale of justice is balanced, it is no longer in favour of
the debtors,'' he said in response to the recent court rulings
allowing commercial banks to auction the property of debtors.
</P>
<P>
A huge portfolio of bad loans forced the Central Bank to close
five small banks among over 50 banks in the country last year and
tarnished the image of the whole sector.
</P>
<P>
Analysts blamed debtors backed by government officials for the
bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem earlier this year criticized the courts for favouring
the debtors and moving too slowly to clear up the debts.
</P>
<P>
However, after rulings were made recently allowing commercial
banks to auction property belonging to several government
ministers with unpaid debts, Cheserem said he now has more
confidence in the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
Public confidence in the banking sector will be further boosted
next year if yields on government paper fall, forcing banks to
compete more fiercely to deliver good customer service, he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor said most small banks have improved their
financial status this year, with 90 percent of them having managed
to increase their minimal capital to 200 million shillings (about
2.7 million U.S. dollars) before December 31, a deadline set by
the Central Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
