<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Adieu, Alain Peyrefitte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- One week ago, if one was asked
who were the top 10 Western personalities who really loved and
understood China, one could not forget Alain Peyrefitte, the
French Academician who has devoted the latter half of his life to
increasing the mutual understanding between France and China.
</P>
<P>
Besides his numerous high-quality books on China, Peyrefitte
was personally engaged in action for China, being a rare voice
speaking for China in his newspaper, Le Figaro, on television and
radio, until the last days of his life.
</P>
<P>
As ``a great friend of China's,'' as Chinese Ambassador to
France Wu Jianmin called him in his message of condolences upon
his death last Saturday, Peyrefitte was one of the people in the
West who stood up for the truth in defending China's achievement
in social and economic development in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In a message of condolences sent to the widow of Peyrefitte,
four former Chinese ambassadors to France said that the
academician had played ``an irreplaceable role'' in developing
Sino-French relations.
</P>
<P>
``What is especially unforgettable is that whenever the
relations between France and China met with difficulties, he
always did not best to help remove the obstacles,'' said the four
former heads of the Chinese mission in Paris.
</P>
<P>
As a political personality, a scholar, a man with a cold
appearance but a warm heart, and a Sinologist, Peyrefitte also
represented a generation of French statesmen around General
Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
``It is a great loss for us, we don't have this kind of
political genius any more,'' said Joel Henri-Fiori, a veteran
French journalist in a telephone interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
``It is a loss for China, because Peyrefitte loves China and
this is special,'' said Bettina Jannink, a free lance journalist
and writer.
</P>
<P>
In his book ``When China Awakes'' published in 1973, Peyrefitte
predicted that China would play a very important role in the world
in the next century and the world should be prepared for it.
</P>
<P>
Like the outstanding French statesman and writer Andre Malraux,
Peyrefitte was among the first French political leaders to have
traveled to New China and met with the first generation of Chinese
leaders, including Premier Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
For many times, Peyrefitte expressed his admiration for the
social and economic achievement made by China since 1949,
especially since China adopted the open and reform policy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
For several times, he stood up in public to dispute those ``
human rights advocates'' who could not but appear ill-read and
badly informed in front of the knowledge and eloquent rhetoric of
the academician.
</P>
<P>
With impeccable dress, manner and respectfulness, Peyrefitte
also drew great admiration from many Chinese diplomats and
journalists working in France.
</P>
<P>
In his monumental work ``Immobile Empire,'' which was inspired
by the trip in the late 18th century by a British mission to
Peking and the only one of his works translated into Chinese,
Peyrefitte showed his great sensibility to the humiliations China
suffered since 1840.
</P>
<P>
Peyrefitte liked to quote in his works Lu Xun, the greatest
Chinese writer of 20th century, who devoted his life for the
modernization of his country.
</P>
<P>
Unlike numerous so-called ``China experts'' in the West, when
writing about China, the academician also showed a great respect
for the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Peyrefitte used to ask his Chinese friends in Paris to check
his works, in order to avoid the slightest mistakes which could
harm the feeling of the Chinese people, said Zhang Hanjun, a
journalist working for the Paris-base Chinese language newspaper ``
Nouvelles d'Europe.''
</P>
<P>
One overseas Chinese poet who lives in Paris published a poem
in memory of Peyrefitte, in which she wrote, ``You are a bridge to
shoulder friendship, and you are a river to let the water of
understanding flow.''
</P>
<P>
Adieu, Alain Peyrefitte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Assembly Urges Israel to Resume Peace Talks With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
General Assembly Wednesday urged Israel to resume peace talks with
Syria and Lebanon and withdraw completely from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly Wednesday morning adopted six resolutions,
two of which are on the situation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
One of the resolutions on the Middle East determined that "the
continued occupation of the Syrian Golan Heights and its de factor
annexation constitute a stumbling block in the way of achieving a
just, comprehensive and lasting peace " in the region.
</P>
<P>
It called on Israel to resume negotiations with Syria and
Lebanon and to respect the commitments reached in previous talks.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demanded that Israel withdraw from all the
occupied Syrian Golan Heights to the line of June 4, 1967, the
border on the eve of Israel's war with its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The second Middle East resolution deplored the transfer by some
states of their diplomatic mission to Jerusalem in violation of a
1980 Security Council resolution and said Israel's decision to
impose its laws and jurisdiction over Jerusalem was illegal.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards Jerusalem as its undivided capital while
Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of a future
Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
