<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Back EU Voting Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain Wednesday offered to
give up one of its two European Commissioners in return for a new
voting system handing more power to member states' ministers,
according to reports here.
</P>
<P>
As the European Union prepares to start the process of
considering allowing up to 12 further nations to join at next week
's Helsinki summit, the British Foreign Office confirmed a change
in procedure would be needed.
</P>
<P>
This could mean reducing the number of commissioners allocated
to larger countries such as Britain, France and Germany, provided
they received a guaranteed larger share of the vote in the Council
of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
A BBC report said that Britain would be prepared to back
qualified-majority voting on some issues, such as transport.
</P>
<P>
But in a speech to the House of Commons Wednesday, Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook made it clear that Britain intended to keep
its right of veto on areas such as taxation, social security and
defense.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Britain would demand a greater voting weight in the
EU's Council of Ministers, which he said was currently skewed
against larger nations and would get more unfavorable for them as
more countries joined.
</P>
<P>
In his speech setting out government policy ahead of next week'
s EU summit in Finland, Cook said Britain would also consider
expanding majority voting in areas "outside key matters of
national interest."
</P>
<P>
"Britain recognizes the importance each member state, however
small, attaches to retaining a seat on the European Commission,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"That is why all the larger member states are willing to
concede their right to a second seat on the Commission," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he also insisted that Britain would not concede its second
seat unless it won agreement to increase its voting strength in
the council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
