<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Hails Mandela's Appointment as Mediator for Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday welcomed the designation by the Eighth Arusha
Regional Summit on Burundi of former South African President
Nelson Mandela as the new facilitator of the Burundi peace process,
a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, told a press conference that
Annan "hopes that the prestige and authority of Mr. Mandela will
reinvigorate the process in Arusha after the death of Mwalimu
Julius Nyerere."
</P>
<P>
"In view of the current political and security situation
prevailing in Burundi, the Secretary-General viewed the
designation of Mandela as a timely decision on the part of the
regional leaders," the spokesman said. "He joined in their call on
all the Burundi parties to extend maximum cooperation to the new
Facilitator towards the successful and urged conclusion of the
peace negotiation."
</P>
<P>
Annan also reiterated his view that "there is no alternative to
a negotiated settlement to the Burundi conflict," and pledged the
United Nation's full support for the new Facilitator, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, 81, replaced Nyerere, the former Tanzanian president
who died in October after trying painstaking effort to promote the
peace process in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Some 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in six years
of civil war in Burundi between Hutu rebels and the government led
by minority ethnic Tutsis. Burundi's civil war began in 1993 when
Tutsi troops murdered the first democratically elected Hutu
president, sparking a series of massacres of both Hutus and Tutsis
in a precursor to the Rwandan genocide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
