<HEADLINE> Europe's Major Stock Markets End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets
finished higher Wednesday, aided by a strong performance on Wall
Street after benign U.S. inflationary data released late in the
day.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 closed near a session high, gaining 49 points,
or 0.7 percent, to 6,646.0 as the UK blue chips index tracked Wall
Street higher.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a pan-European gauge of key blue chips,
reflected the late rally as it closed almost 1 percent higher at 1,
450.74.
</P>
<P>
Telecom stocks rebounded after a weak session Tuesday, helped
by further merger activity after a Scandinavian-led bid in the
Irish telecom sector.
</P>
<P>
BT surged 5.5 percent to 1,320 pence, helped by Deutsche Bank
raising its price target on the stock to 1,700 pence. Rival CW
rose 2.9 percent and VoD gained 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The newly renamed telecom equipment manufacturer, Marconi, was
the biggest winner among UK blue chips as it continued its re-
rating as a pure technology stock. It soared 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's electronically traded Xetra Dax closed 38 points
higher at 5,933.84, a rise of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shares of Mannesmann rose 3.4 percent in volatile trade as the
company's chief executive said he had secured the backing of a
large number of shareholders in the company's efforts to rebuff
the hostile bid from Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 posted a matching 0.7 percent gain as it
closed 40 points higher at 5,381.41. One of the leading gainers
was pay-TV giant Canal Plus, which surged 5.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
