<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Million Nigerians to be Infected by AIDS in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- As Nigerians joined the rest of
the world to mark the 12th World AIDS Day on Wednesday, they were
startled by the fact that the killer disease was spreading at a
rate of one person per minute in their country.
</P>
<P>
Drawing a dismal picture, the country's Health Minister Tim
Menakaya said at a special event to mark the day in the country's
capital Abuja that by the end of 1999, "over half a million new
infections would have occurred, " while some 4.9 million people
are expected to be afflicted with the virus by 2003.
</P>
<P>
From an unknown disease a few years ago, AIDS has risen right
to the top of Nigerian health agenda, the minister said. A recent
survey shows that the first AIDS patient in the country was found
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Nigeria, the country with the largest
population in Africa, is also said to have more than 600,000 AIDS
orphans, a quarter of whom have died for lack of care.
</P>
<P>
The overall national average of prevalence increased from 1.8
percent in 1990 to 3.8 percent in 1993, 4.5 percent in 1995 and
5.4 percent in 1999, with women in their early 20's having the
highest level of infection.
</P>
<P>
Although Nigeria is still less severely affected by the
epidemic than eastern and southern African countries, its
population of more than 108 million means that it already has more
people infected with the HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
"This is bound to have a major socio-economic impact on
Nigerian society, including reduced life expectancy, increased
burden of medical care, increase in the number of orphans and
decline in economic growth," according to a report on the
country's AIDS situation.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still hope if relevant intervention programs
could be strengthened through a strong national commitment,
political will and the support of development partners, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Dwelling on a worldwide theme of the World AIDS Day "learn and
live! World AIDS campaign with children and young people," the
Nigerian government called on its citizens Wednesday to join the
fight against the pandemic with renewed focus on the fate of
children, the future of the country.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo and his administration have pledged
more support for an anti-AIDS drive for which the government has
increased its budgetary allocation for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The president has promised to make the fight against AIDS a
priority despite his other challenges in ending murderous ethnic
conflicts and reviving a moribund economy.
</P>
<P>
"President Obasanjo said that he was determined to personally
lead the national war against the scourge," a statement from the
presidency said on Wednesday, adding that a comprehensive program
would soon be put in place.
</P>
<P>
A report from the United Nations, used as a global index of the
disease, estimated that a cumulative total of 13 million children,
most of them in Africa, would have lost their mothers or both
parents to AIDS by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The disease has reportedly killed more than 16 million people
worldwide, 2.2 million of them in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Indicators of U.S. Economy Remain Flat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of
Leading Economic Indicators in the United States remained flat in
October, The Conference Board, the prominent research group, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said in a report that the index was 107.9
in October, the same as in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
"The flatness in the leading economic series is especially
surprising because it centers on weak indicators of manufacturing
activity," said Conference Board Economist Ken Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
"It was thought that with trade conditions improving, the
manufacturing sector would finally start strengthening. Weak trade
conditions had been a milestone around the manufacturing sector
ever since the 'Asia Flu' developed. But foreign economies now
seem to be recovering. The October decline in orders may not be
the result of lags between foreign recoveries and nay subsequent
ordering."
</P>
<P>
Goldstein said "if this is the case, more orders early in 2000
may strengthen the leading economic indicators in the same way
that declines flattened the series in September and October."
</P>
<P>
The report said, five of the ten indicators that make up the
leading index rose in October. The most significant increases are
building permits and interest rate spread. The most significant
negative contributors to the composite leading index in October
are manufacturers' new orders of consumer goods and materials and
consumer expectations, it added.
</P>
<P>
The indicator serves as a barometer of U.S. economic trends up
to six months in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Gives Green Light to PVC Toy Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) member
states unanimously gave the green light Wednesday to a precedent
setting EU-wide emergency ban on soft PVC teething toys.
</P>
<P>
The EU emergency ban, proposed by the European Commission,
includes new products ordered by retailers. The Commission, the EU
executive branch, said that the products on the shelves are "
liable to present a serious and immediate risk to health."
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Product Safety Emergencies, comprised of
officials from all 15 EU member states, unanimously supported the
Commission's proposal to ban six toxic softeners found in soft PVC
toys marketed for teething.
</P>
<P>
The ban, first debated in May 1998, is the first emergency
product ban in the European Union. Now the European Commission can
formally adopt the decision at its meeting next week. Then the EU
member states have to take all necessary measures to implement the
decision within less than 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greenpeace warned consumers that shopkeepers are not
obliged to remove banned products from the shelves, and that the
ban does not cover all soft PVC toys for children under three.
</P>
<P>
"The emergency ban confirms what Greepeace has been saying for
more than two years - that soft PVC toys are dangerous to the
health of small children," said Axel Singhofen, Greenpeace EU
Adviser, in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"But as a result of the narrow scope of this ban, and the lack
of a mandatory market withdrawal of banned toys, consumers are now
faced with chaos, unable to tell whether the toys they are buying
are PVC with toxic softeners or not," he said.
</P>
<P>
"An immediate market withdrawal of all soft PVC toys and
childcare articles for children under three is the only way that
babies in Europe can be protected from a new round of hazardous
Christmas presents," Singhofen said. "And it is the only way that
retailers can regain their reputation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Announces Sovereign Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua President Arnold
Aleman on Wednesday announced that his country will apply a 30
percent sovereign tax on imports from Honduras and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua made the decision to protest the ratification of a
maritime treaty singed between Honduras and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Honduras congress on Tuesday night unanimously ratified the
treaty signed with Colombia in 1986. Honduras also announced it
was moving 2,000 troops to areas near the Nicaraguan border to
prevent timber smuggling. Honduras denied the two moves were
related.
</P>
<P>
In the treaty, Bogota recognizes that Honduras' sea border with
Nicaragua is parallel 15, while Managua considers that its limits
in this zone are on parallel 17.
</P>
<P>
Between these two parallels are about 30,000 square kilometers
Nicaragua holds it will loss under the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua also claims rights over islands east to the 78th
meridian. Colombia claims its own rights extend west to the 82nd
meridian, based on a 1928 treaty which Nicaragua claims was forced
upon it by a U.S. occupation force at the time.
</P>
<P>
"The treaty in question damages Nicaragua and intends to
deliver or recognize Nicaraguan territory to third counties", said
Nicaraguan Foreign Minister Eduardo Montealegre on Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Aleman also ordered to close border to Honduras' Port
Cortes, where has been used many Nicaraguan firms as export exits.
</P>
<P>
But Aleman ruled out the possibility of military actions in the
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991202.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeking Support for U.N. Draft Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
said Wednesday that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright would be
trying to muster support for a U.N. draft resolution aimed at
getting weapons inspectors into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect that Secretary Albright will have a number of
conversations in the coming days on this resolution, including
with the French foreign minister, the Russian foreign minister,
the British foreign minister and others," spokesman James Rubin
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has stopped any weapons
inspections in his country since the United States and Britain
launched air strikes against his country last December.
</P>
<P>
Washington has tried many ways in vain to re-enter the country
under the name of weapons inspections, and the draft resolution is
the latest.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz repeated Iraq's objections to
the draft resolution during his visit to Russia recently.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated Iraq's objections to a short extension of a U.
N. oil-for-food program meant as an interim measure until a
broader resolution on lifting sanctions against Iraq is agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
