<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise On Slower Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose
Wednesday as the latest reports indicated that the U.S. economic
growth is continuing at a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 120.58 at 10,998.39,
diminishing its losses of 130.36 points in the previous three
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor
's 500 index rose 8.81 at 1,397.72 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index rose 17.55 at 3,353.71.
</P>
<P>
Stocks rose as the Conference Board reported that its
Composite Index of Leading Economic Indicators remained flat in
October, staying at 107.9, the same as in the previous, while the
National Association of Purchasing Management said its index of
manufacturing activity dropped from 56.6 in October to 56.2 in
November.
</P>
<P>
The two reports showed signs that the tightening monetary
policy of the Federal Reserve may be working. The Federal Reserve
has raised interest rates three times this year in an effort to
cool off the economy.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 3.59 at 634.77 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 1.77 at 834.58. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 0.41 at 453.67.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,708 down, 1,407 up and 427
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 881.52 million shares from 966.56
million in the previous session. 
</P>
